{[%evp 0,9,43,20,27,6,10,14,14,-13,4,19]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 {Welcome dear chess players in our "1.d4 according to Dreev" series. In the previous database, we have seen the 4...c5 and the 4...dxc4 Catalan. In this database, we will analyze the moves 4...Be7 and 4...Bb4+, which are arguably Black's most popular options. The material is divided into 6 Units, and we gave a lot of space for the video lessons because it will be extremely important for you to follow the video lessons to better understand the ideas, the plans, and the way of thinking in each position. At the end of the database, you will find 30 exercises to test yourself.} Be7 {This is the so-called "Classical line".} (4... Bb4+ {This is a very solid option for Black, and a very common one. My recommendation is} 5. Nbd2 {Because it allows us to get less known positions, where there is more space for creativity and to outplay your opponents. Black can play with dxc4 or in solid style with 00 and then maybe b6-Bb7. We'll consider all these variations in Unit 6.}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 {Is Black's main continuation.} (6... c6 {This move leads to the so-called "Closed Catalan." Understanding the move orders and plans is extremely important in these positions. I will tell you when it's the moment to study concrete theory and when it's the moment to evaluate the position from the strategic perspective.} 7. Qc2 b6 {This is the "Modern closed Catalan". What is the difference compared to 7...Nbd7? It's huge, and we'll discuss it in Unit 2.} (7... Nbd7 {This is the "Old closed Catalan", and we'll discuss it in Unit 1.})) (6... a5 {This move became very popular recently. I call it "Tajmanov variation". We'll discuss it in Unit 2.}) 7. Qc2 b5 {This is Black's second most important option. After} (7... c6 {This move became famous after the game So-Mamedyarov, Candidates 2018. I will tell you my opinion about it in Unit 3.}) (7... b6 {Another modern variation. We'll discuss it in Unit 3 together with the moves c5 and b6.}) (7... c5 {This move is not so common, but it's not a bad one. We'll discuss it in Unit 3.}) (7... a6 {This is Black's most common move, and we'll discuss it in Unit 5. My recommendation will be to go for a not-so-popular direction, where it's very unlikely that your opponent will be well-prepared, and where playing with White it's much more interesting. I will say you immediately, against 7...a6 doesn't exist any way to get an advantage with White, because this is probably Black's most sound line in all the Catalan. Our philosophy will be to create the maximum number of unpleasant problems for our opponents and to go for positions where we can play for a long game.}) 8. a4 {Black has two completely different approaches, and we'll discuss both of them in Unit 4.} b4 {This move leads to very fascinating complications, my recommendation is} (8... Bb7 {Very solid line. Black is ready to play a pawn-down endgame, but he hopes to concretely make a draw.}) 9. Nfd2 {And here Black has a lot of lines, but I have managed to invent extremely challenging ideas in all of them. This is not a line that every player can try from the Black's side, but it's a line which is played only by extremely strong theoreticians. Well, when you will face one of them, I am very curious to see how they will react to my new ideas!} *

