{[%evp 0,23,20,18,17,13,13,12,20,-9,2,0,0,0,19,16,14,14,21,0,-3,-2,23,22,25,21]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 (6... a5 $5 {It's a new variation, recently played by many strong players. We will continue with} 7. Qc2 Nc6 8. a3 dxc4 9. Qxc4 a4 10. Nc3 {[%csl Ra4]} Bd7 11. Bf4 {And Alexey will analyze it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) (6... c6 7. Qc2 b6 (7... Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {[%csl Yd2][%cal Ge2e4] Against the Nbd7 move order, Nbd2 is a very simple and straight-forward way. Our idea is to prepare e2-e4.} b6 (8... Re8 $6 {[%csl Rc8] This is a slow and harmless move. Black's priority is to solve the Bc8 problem, that's why 8...Re8 is not a good way.} 9. e4 $1 {We play the typical idea of the position.} dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 {[%csl Rc8] And Black's position is much worse because of the Bc8 problem.} Nf6 {Black's most common continuation, and this position was reached more than 400 times, but after} (11... e5 $1 {Is the best, according to the engine, but it shows how bad Black's position is.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bc5 14. Be3 Qb6 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Re5] Black can try to hold, but we have an extra pawn, and the situation is obviously very good for us. If this is Black's best position, then it means that 8...Re8 is not a good move.}) (11... Bf6 {[%cal Ye6e5] Black prepares e5, but he will never be in time to play it:} 12. Re1 e5 13. Bf4 $1 $16) 12. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Re6e5,Yc6c5,Yf1d1,Gb7b6,Gf3e5] White's position is much better. Black has the Bc8 problem, he can never play b6, he can never play e5, and in case of c5, we can play Rd1 with a huge advantage.}) (8... c5 {This move has some sense, but why did Black not play it at move 7, then?} 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. b4 $5 Nce4 {necessary move.} (10... Ncd7 11. a3 $14 {Just better for White.}) 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 (11... dxe4 $2 12. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Rd8]}) 12. Rb1 {Black's position is not lost, but it's passive. For example:} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] best move.} 13. Rd1 Bb7 14. Nd4 {[%cal Gg2e4] Bxe4 is already a threat.} Qc8 (14... Qc7 $2 15. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 15. Be3 $14) (8... dxc4 $2 {In this concrete position, dxc4 is a very bad move, after} 9. Nxc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc8] We have a fantastic position, and Black still has the Bc8 problem.} b6 $2 {Is never possible because of} 10. Nfe5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 9. e4 Bb7 (9... Ba6 {This move is possible, but it's very rare, and it doesn't have a clear logic. If Black wants to play with Ba6, then it's much better for him to start with 7...b6 and Ba6 immediately.} 10. e5 Ne8 11. Re1 {We will see it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) (9... dxe4 {This move was played in more than 2000 games. It's a move with a lot of historical games, but nowadays, it's clear that this is not the best way for Black.} 10. Nxe4 {[%csl Rc8] Black generally has the problem of his Bc8. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (9... dxc4 {This move is very important, but it will be even more important in another lesson, with a slightly different position.} 10. Nxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is ready for c6-c5. We'll discuss it in "Position 5" of this Unit.} 11. h4) 10. e5 ({Be careful to don't start with} 10. cxd5 cxd5 {because after} 11. e5 {Black can play} Ne4 $1 {(also 11...Rc8 and then Ne4 is fine for him)}) 10... Ne8 11. cxd5 {This position was important for the Catalan many years ago.} exd5 {This is probably the best recapture, but also the less common one.} (11... cxd5 {was played in 1000 games. White's position is better, but it's useful to know the typical ideas.} 12. Re1 $1 {[%csl Yf1][%cal Yg2f1,Yd2f1,Gh2h4,Gf1h2,Gf3g5,Gc1g5] White's best move. Re1 is very useful against Ba6 ideas, but it also frees the f1 square for the knight or for the bishop. We'll discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 12. Re1 {[%csl Ge6,Yf5][%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Yd2f1,Yf1e3,Ye3f5] Black usually transfers his knight on e6, and we transfer our one to f5. We'll discuss it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) 8. Rd1 {We need to play Rd1, that's why 7...b6 is a completely different variation compared to 7...Nbd7.} (8. Nbd2 {This was good against 7...Nbd7, but against 7...b6 is not great because Black can play} c5 $1 $132 {And his position is immediately very good.}) 8... Nbd7 {[%csl Yc8] This is a tricky move because Black still has not committed to his Bc8 development.} (8... Ba6 {Interesting concrete move. We can play now} 9. Ne5 $5 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Ye2e4] White the idea to stop Black's development. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (8... Bb7 {[%csl Yb7] Now that Black's bishop is already on b7, we can go for} 9. Nc3 (9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. e4) 9... Nbd7 (9... dxc4 {not dangerous because of} 10. Ne5 $14 {and we are slightly better.}) 10. b3 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our idea. We prepare e4, and let's see how Black will continue. We'll discuss this in "Position 2" of this Unit. Transposes to 8...Bb7.} ({we don't play} 10. e4 {because of} dxc4 {Where there are a lot of high-level games, and Black's position is absolutely fine.})) 9. b3 {[%cal Ya7a5] We start with b3, and we'll analyze this in "Position 3" of this Unit.} (9. Nc3 {is not good now because Black can play} Ba6 $1 $11 {[%csl Ga6]}) (9. Nbd2 {[%csl Yd1] once again, this is nothing because of} Bb7 {[%csl Gd1]} 10. e4 dxc4 11. Nxc4 c5 $132) 9... Ba6 {Now that Black's bishop is on a6, we will play} (9... Bb7 10. Nc3 {Transposes to 8...Bb7.}) (9... a5 $5 {As we will see, this move has a very hidden positional idea.}) 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Ya8c8,Yc6c5] Black can try here Rc8 or c5.}) 7. Qc2 a6 (7... c5 {[%csl Rc8] This move is a principled move from the strategic perspective. The only problem for Black is that it will be difficult to develop his bishop on c8.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Qxc4 Qe7 $1 {This is Black's best continuation, and my recommendation is} 10. Rd1 $5 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] A move that was played only once. We will check it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (7... c6 {This move has a very solid reputation.} 8. a4 $5 {This is my recommendation. I don't want to say that 8.a4 is stronger than 8.Qxc4, but there are much fewer games, and it's easier to surprise our opponent.} (8. Qxc4 {Is by far White's most common continuation, but a lot of games here, and you can check the model game So-Mamedyarov, Candidates 2018.} b5) 8... b6 {This looks as Black's most logical continuation, and now we will play} 9. Na3 $5 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ga3c4] My idea is to capture on c4 with the knight. We will check it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) (7... b5 8. a4 b4 (8... Bb7 {This move is the cause of headache for many theoreticians, but I know that there are many players who are happy to face it. Why? Because Black usually plays positions with pawn down, where if you check with the engine, the engine is optimistic saying it is a draw, but over the board, Black sometimes doesn't achieve the draw.} 9. axb5 a6 10. bxa6 {This is the most principled continuation. Now, Black should try to prove his compensation for the pawn.} (10. Nc3 {This is the kind of line you play for one game.} axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 Bd5 {And you can try to find something new, for one or two games. Black is fine in more than one way and in the best case, White achieves a +0.20 advantage, which is not huge. So I decided it is not practical.}) 10... Nxa6 11. Qxc4 {[%csl Gb2,Rc7,Gd4] So we have an extra pawn, but Black has activity and the play is really move by move.} Bd5 {[%cal Yc4d3,Yc4c2,Ga6b4]} 12. Qc3 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ra6b4] This is the only challenging move. The queen is sidestepping Black's gain of a tempo based on ...Nb4. The following sequence is pretty forced} c5 {The best move.} (12... Ne4 $6 {Is not so good, because we have the e3 square for our queen.} 13. Qe3 $1 {We will check it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 13. Be3 (13. Bf4 {This was played by Carlsen, and it is a one game idea. Black is fine in more than one way, so you need to invest a lot of work.} Ne4 14. Qc1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxf2 $5 {Even this tactic is possible.} (15... Nb4 {was played by Saric against Rapport, and I couldn't find anything.}) (15... Nec5 $6 {was Radjabov's choice, but it is not a good move.}) 16. Rxf2 {Now forced simplifications.} Bxg2 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Kxg2 Nb4 19. Rxa8 Qxa8+ 20. Rf3 Nd5 $11 {Black is fine.}) 13... Ne4 {[%cal Rc3e3] Now it is a good move, no more Qe3.} 14. Qe1 (14. Qc1 {I don't like.} cxd4 $11) 14... Nb4 (14... Qb6 $6 {was played in one game, but now} 15. Qc1 $1 cxd4 16. Bxd4 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gb1c3] And the tempo and the extra pawn, makes a big difference.}) 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Nc3 {We are down to 26 games, 18 continued with Nxc3 and 8 with Nc2.} Nxc3 (16... Nc2 {Is, in my opinion, less precise because we can play} 17. Nxd5 $1 {And we will discuss it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 17. bxc3 (17. Qxc3 c4 $44 {Black has positional compensation.}) 17... Nc2 {This is Black's best continuation, and we will discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.} 18. Qd2 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 cxd4 20. cxd4 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1g2]}) 9. Nfd2 {This is the most interesting line, in my opinion.} (9. Ne5 {Is White's most common and concrete try. We will discuss about it separately.}) 9... Nd5 {Nowadays, everybody plays Nd5.} (9... b3 {normal move, but very rare and it's unlikely you will face it. If Black plays it, then you will just have a playable position. We'll check it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) (9... c6 {This move is not so common nowadays, because after} 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2b3] Black has problems with the queen, and we play for domination. We will discuss it in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) 10. Nxc4 c5 {without c5, our position is just better.} (10... Ba6 $2 11. Rd1 $16 {clear advantage}) (10... Nc6 $2 11. e3 $16 {clear advantage.}) 11. dxc5 {Black has two options: Bxc5 or Ba6.} Ba6 {Black's most common continuation.} (11... Bxc5 {less common, but it became a very serious engine-style line.} 12. e4 Nb6 {necessary} 13. Ncd2 $1 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ga4a5,Ge4e5] White's best try. We will see in "Position 6" of this Unit that Black can play 11...Bxc5 only if he remembers an endless amount of concrete computer variations.}) 12. Ne3 Nd7 $1 {Only move.} 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. c6 {This leads to very complicated and sharp positions. We will discuss it in "Position 7" of this Unit.}) (7... b6 {This move is very popular nowadays.} 8. Bg5 {This is my recommendation.} (8. Ne5 {I don't like this direction because it gets too concrete after} Qxd4 9. Bxa8 Qxe5 $44 {Black needs to play some best moves, but he will be fine. In my opinion, if your opponent plays 7...b6, then for sure he is well parepared against 8.Ne5, that's why I don't want to enter in this line.}) 8... Nd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbd2 {Now, Black has three options.} b5 {This is probably Black's best continuation, but not all players are ready to play it. My idea will be to play} (10... Bb7 {Bb7 is a normal move, but the good thing for us is that it's not so concrete.} 11. Nxc4 Nd7 12. a3 $1 {[%cal Rd5b4,Ge2e4] We stop Nb4 and we are ready for e4. We will check it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) (10... Ba6 {[%csl Ya6] Black's bishop on a6 might be more active than on b7.} 11. Nxc4 c5 12. Rac1 {is my recommendation, and we will check it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) 11. h4 $5 h6 12. b3 {[%cal Yc4b3,Yc4c3] Only one game was played here, and we will check this in "Position 5" of this Unit. Black's two options are 12...c3 and 12...cxb3.}) 8. Rd1 $5 {This is an intriguing and underexplored idea, with only about 150 games in the database. This line has been a favorite of the creative GM Daniil Dubov, who used it several times, including in his match against Magnus Carlsen.} b5 $1 {This is undoubtedly Black's best continuation and, if you think about it, the only drawback of our move 8.Rd1 compared to the mainline 8.a4.} (8... Bd7 {[%csl Gd1] This is Black’s strongest continuation in the mainline with 8.a4, but here it’s questionable because, against Bd7, White’s Rd1 proves far more effective than the move a4.} 9. Ne5 $1 Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Qxc4 $16 {[%csl Gd1,Yd4] Thanks to the move 8.Rd1, our pawn on d4 is not hanging.}) (8... Nbd7 {Black can play many moves like this, and they are all not critical. We will speak about Nbd7 and other sidelines when analyzing the "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 9. Ne5 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gg2a8] We activate our bishop, and Black now has two logical continuations.} Nd5 {This is Black’s most common continuation. Unlike the alternative 9...c6, Black aims to keep the long diagonal open for the bishop, hoping that once Bb7 is played, it will be more active without the c7-c6 move blocking its potential.} (9... c6 {This was Magnus Calrsen's choice. We will play the typical} 10. b3 $5 cxb3 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Yd1][%cal Gg2c6,Ge5c6,Gc2c6,Ga1a6] We sacrificed a pawn, but we have fantastic pieces. We will discuss this in depth in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 10. b3 {This is the typical idea of the 8.Rd1 variation.} cxb3 {by far the most common continuation.} (10... Bb7 $5 {This move is very rare in practice, but it's possible according to the engine. After} 11. bxc4 Nb4 $1 {Black may be able to hold if he will find all the best moves. We will discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 11. axb3 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Ya1a6] Of course, we recapture with the pawn, at least because our a1 rook is now working.} Bb7 {Standard move. Difficult to imagine that Black will play something else.} 12. Ba3 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Yc5,Ye7] Without Ba3, our compensation becomes uncertain. Why is Ba3 a strong move? -By exchanging the dark-squared bishops, we can gain control over the critical c5 square. -Our bishop lacks a productive square, while Black’s dark-squares bishop could become significantly more effective than ours.} ({For example, I don't like a move like} 12. Bb2 {because of:} Nb4 13. Qc3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qd5+ {Black has no problems, and maybe he already has some advantage.}) 12... Bxa3 {Most natural and popular move.} (12... Bd6 {[%cal Ra3d6,Gc7d6] This is a tricky move because Black does not allow the bishop's exchange. Of course, Bxd6 is not good because of cxd6.} 13. Nd3 {We play this standard idea and we have a very strong compensation for the pawn. We will consider this in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) (12... a5 {While not theoretically critical, this move has been tested by strong GMs like Yu and Vocaturo, so we’ll explore it in 'Position 6' of this Unit.}) {after} 13. Nxa3 $44 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ge5d3,Gd3c5] We have a very interesting positional compensation. I could even go further by saying that we have a positional initiative! We will consider it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} *

