he Bc8 problem.} b6 $2 {Is never possible because of} 10. Nfe5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc6]}) 9. e4 Bb7 (9... Ba6 {This move is possible, but it's very rare, and it doesn't have a clear logic. If Black wants to play with Ba6, then it's much better for him to start with 7...b6 and Ba6 immediately.} 10. e5 Ne8 11. Re1 {We will see it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) (9... dxe4 {This move was played in more than 2000 games. It's a move with a lot of historical games, but nowadays, it's clear that this is not the best way for Black.} 10. Nxe4 {[%csl Rc8] Black generally has the problem of his Bc8. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (9... dxc4 {This move is very important, but it will be even more important in another lesson, with a slightly different position.} 10. Nxc4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is ready for c6-c5. We'll discuss it in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) 10. e5 ({Be careful to don't start with} 10. cxd5 cxd5 {because after} 11. e5 {Black can play} Ne4 $1 {(also 11...Rc8 and then Ne4 is fine for him)}) 10... Ne8 11. cxd5 {This position was important for the Catalan many years ago.} exd5 {This is probably the best recapture, but also the less common one.} (11... cxd5 {was played in 1000 games. White's position is better, but it's useful to know the typical ideas.} 12. Re1 $1 {[%csl Yf1][%cal Yg2f1,Yd2f1] White's best move. Re1 is very useful against Ba6 ideas, but it also frees the f1 square for the knight or for the bishop. We'll discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 12. Re1 {[%csl Ge6,Yf5][%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Yd2f1,Yf1e3,Ye3f5] Black usually transfers his knight on e6, and we transfer our one to f5. We'll discuss it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} *

