{[%evp 0,49,27,35,22,-9,-4,-11,-11,-35,1,-16,2,0,22,12,11,-5,-2,5,12,39,13,-7,-9,-43,-35,-35,-21,-93,-70,-49,-32,-67,-29,-70,-37,-77,4,-131,-114,-73,-73,-104,-107,-89,-89,-73,-73,-38,-55,-36]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4 dxc4 {The most critical line. It was played for the first time on the high level by Adams in 2006. It was forgotten for many years, until recently, around 2018-2019, people understood the value of this line and became very popular on the high level.} 10. Nxc4 Bb7 {Now White has played a lot of moves.} (10... c5 $4 {huge mistake.} 11. Ng5 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rh7][%cal Ge4e5,Yg2a8,Yc2h7]}) 11. h4 $5 {is our recommendation, fantastic move, this is very useful in many Catalan position.} (11. Rd1 {Very important: We don't play Rd1, because after} c5 $1 {Black's position is absolutely fine.} 12. e5 {is the best chance for White.} Nd5 13. Qe4 b5 {looks as the strongest, now White can go for some complications.} 14. Nd6 Bxd6 15. Ng5 g6 16. exd6 N7f6 {I don't see any idea for White, plus Black is not forced to enter this complication, other moves except 13...b5 exist.} 17. Qe5 c4 18. a4 b4 $132 {Maybe you can try it for one game, but actually if things go well for Black, Black can try for the full point also.}) (11. Ne3 {is a very funny variation, we need to check it.} c5 12. d5 exd5 13. exd5 {is the critical move.} (13. e5 {is no problem for Black.} Ne8 14. Nf5 Nc7 $15 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gc7e6] Black is even slightly better.}) 13... Nxd5 {Now a forced variation.} 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Rd1 Be6 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. Rxd8 Raxd8 {We achieve this by force, now} 18. Be4 {is the best move.} Bg4 {[%cal Ge5f3] Alexey and I both agree, that Black's compensation is fantastic. Our king is potentially weak and it is not easy to play.} (18... h6 {also possible.}) 19. Kg2 {is met with} Bd1 $132 {And some problems with the queen.}) (11. Bf4 $5 {My first idea was to offer you this, but I analyzed it with Alexey and we understood that it is quite empty.} c5 {Necessary.} 12. Rfe1 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Ye4][%cal Ye1e4] This was the starting idea.} cxd4 13. Nd6 $1 {Now both sides enter a forced variation.} Bxd6 14. Bxd6 d3 $1 15. Qxd3 {Now Black has the important trick} Bxe4 {[%cal Re1e4,Gd7c5]} 16. Qd4 e5 17. Qa4 Re8 18. Rad1 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 e4 20. Bxe4 Nxe4 21. Rxe4 Rxe4 22. Qxe4 Nc5 23. Qf3 Ne6 {You can argue that White has chances thanks to the bishop, but it is absolutely empty.} 24. Bc5 {Putting the bishop on e3 is the maximum White can do.} Qe8 25. Be3 {Three high level games, all 3 ended in a draw, very nominal edge, but you will never win this position even against lower rated.} Rd8 $11 {That's the reason why I do not recommend 11.Bf4.}) 11... h6 {is a normal move, but now we can use improved lines of the position we have seen without the h4-h6 inclusion.} (11... c5 {[%csl Yh4] Black may think that if White spent a move on h4, they can just continue their plan, but the pawn is very useful on h4.} 12. e5 Nd5 {Now White has a lot of moves, but in the end we chose 13.dxc5.} 13. dxc5 {Black has a choice: to capture or not to capture.} Nxc5 {is our main move.} (13... Qc7 $5 {was played in the game Finek-Dotzer, EU-ch U14 Prague 2024, actually both players are very young, I played against Dotzer this year and he is only 13, but a strong player already, also this Qc7 idea is quite interesting. White could have played} 14. Ng5 $146 {attacking mate.} Bxg5 (14... g6 {possible, but now some squares are weak.} 15. Ne4 Nxe5 {is the best.} 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Re1 {Some threats against the queen, how to play with Black? Not clear at all.} bxc5 18. Bh6 Nb4 {Black needs to be a genius already.} (18... Rfc8 19. Rad1 $16 {Engine thinks that White is already better.}) 19. Qb1 Rfd8 20. Nf6+ {Who will allow it? So Nb4 not an easy move.} Qxf6 21. Bxb7 Rab8 22. Bg5 {Engine says this line, and doesn't think that it is equal, but White is slightly better.} Qg7 23. Bxe7 Rd7 24. Bxc5 Rbxb7 25. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Gc5,Yf6,Yg7,Yh6] Not so much, but still more pleasant for us, and it is still not easy to play with Black. Best move is Nd5 allowing Bd4. So you see.}) 15. hxg5 $5 Qxc5 {Logical move.} 16. Qe4 Rab8 {[%csl Gb7,Yd5] To defend the bishop and jump with the knight.} 17. Nd6 Ba8 18. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1f4] Now it is very tough to understand what to do with Black. For the engine, the best line continues:} Rfd8 {Already some may be scared to leave f7 weak.} 19. Bf4 Nxf4 20. gxf4 {[%csl Gd6] White has a fantastic knight and pawns, if Black plays a human move:} Bxg2 $2 {is already mistake.} 21. Kxg2 $40 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Gg2g3] White can play Kg3 next, the king is very safe there, some attack on the h-file is possible.}) (13... Bxc5 $6 {allows} 14. Ng5 {Black cannot even take on g5.} g6 15. Ne4 $16) (13... bxc5 $6 {Obviously we don't need to check.} 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. hxg5 $16 {Better structure, very good position for us.}) 14. Bg5 {How to play with Black is a good question.} Nb4 {If Black wants to play it, better to do it immediately.} (14... Bxg5 $2 15. Nxg5 $18) (14... h6 {We can play a long game after} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%csl Gd6] The d6 square is weak.} 16. Rfd1 {[%csl Yc4] We don't need to rush with Nd6, the knight stays well on c4 for now.} Nb4 {is the best move, but I will not check it, it is not important.} (16... Ba6 17. Nd4 $16 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gc4d6,Ra8c8,Rf8d8] Terrible position for Black.}) (16... Rac8 17. Nd6 $16 {with tempo and we take the bishop.}) 17. Qd2 a5 {Who will play like this?} 18. Qd6 $14 {For the engine is holdable, but over the board is difficult for Black.}) 15. Qe2 Bxg5 {looks logical.} (15... Ba6 {For me it is not clear the point of this move, Black stops Nd6 maybe, but now we can play.} 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Nd4 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3] We can play slowly, and for sure White is preferable. How much is another story.}) 16. Rfd1 $1 {Nice intermezzo.} (16. hxg5 $6 Qd3 $1 $132 {is the idea.}) 16... Qc7 17. hxg5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc4d6] is our recommendation, now Nd6 is a huge threat, so only move is} (17. Nxg5 {can also be considered.} Bxg2 18. Kxg2 h6 19. Nf3 Rad8 20. Nd6 {For sure White has the more pleasant position.} Nb7 {With the idea to change the knights.} 21. a3 Nd5 22. Ne4 {We go back.} Qe7 (22... Nc5 23. Rac1 $36 {looks unpleasant for Black.}) 23. Nd4 Rc8 24. Rd2 $5 $14 {[%cal Re7c7] Other moves are also fine, somewhere we can double on the d file or push f4 etc.}) 17... Ba6 {preventing it.} 18. Rd4 {[%cal Gd4h4] Black needs to understand how to play.} Rad8 19. Rh4 {looks very interesting, maybe not advantage, but interesting.} Qd7 {[%cal Gd7d3] The best.} 20. Bf1 Qd3 21. Qxd3 Nbxd3 22. Rb1 $14 {Not so bad for Black, but of course playable for White and we are very far.}) (11... b5 $146 {I checked this move also, although nobody played it.} 12. Ne3 c5 13. e5 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 {And now we have} 15. Ng5 {That's the idea of h4 of course.} Bxg5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Bxg5 {White has dxc5 and Be7 ideas.} Qc8 18. dxc5 {It is easier to take.} (18. Be7 {Black is lucky to have} cxd4 $14 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gf8c8] Still it is slightly better for White.}) 18... Re8 {Black prepares for Nxc5 or e5.} 19. Rad1 Nxe5 {Black needs to take on e5 at some moment.} 20. Qb3 Qxc5 21. Rxd5 {This is actually pressure, we can put pressure.} Qc4 22. Qxc4 bxc4 23. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc1c2] The endgame is interesting for White, plus we are very far into a novelty.}) 12. Ne3 {Now this move is stronger.} c5 13. d5 exd5 14. e5 $1 {With the pawns back on h2 an h7, Black was absolutely fine, here it is different.} (14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rd1 Be6 17. Ne5 Nxe5) 14... Nh7 {[%csl Yg8,Yh7] is a more useful move, the knight will defend the king sometimes.} (14... Ne8 $6 {[%csl Gh2,Gh7] was great in the previous line, but not here.} 15. Rd1 {We can start with 15.Nf5 also, but this is stronger.} Nc7 16. Nf5 Ne6 {[%csl Rh6] And now because the pawn is on h6, White has} 17. Bxh6 $1 {We can sacrifice the piece.} gxh6 18. Nxh6+ Kh8 (18... Kg7 $6 19. Nf5+ Kg8 20. Nh2 $18 {[%cal Gg2d5,Gc2e2,Ge2g4] White has a winning attack.}) 19. Qf5 $1 {Only move for advantage, but enough.} Ng7 20. Nxf7+ Rxf7 21. Qxf7 {We are up in material.} Qf8 22. Qg6 Qf5 23. Qxf5 Nxf5 {The endgame is also fine, we have fantastic pieces.} 24. Ng5 {Not easy to protect d5.} Nd4 {Only move.} 25. f4 $16 {We have 4 passed pawns, I want to see how Black can defend this position. Engine says it is +1.}) 15. Nf5 Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8c6,Gc6h6] Only move. Not an easy one to find, the idea is Rc6 to defend the 6th rank.} (15... Re8 $2 {Very big mistake, because it leaves f7 weak.} 16. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 17. Nxh6+ Kg7 18. Nxf7 {We have 2 pawns for the bishop.} Qc8 {is the only move apparently.} 19. e6 {White's attack is too strong.} Ndf8 20. Rae1 Bf6 (20... Nxe6 $2 21. Bh3 $18) 21. Nd6 $18 {White recovers material, with a winning position.}) (15... Kh8 $2 {Maybe somebody will play this, but it is also a mistake.} 16. Re1 {White has a big advantage already.} Rc8 17. e6 fxe6 18. Rxe6 Rf7 19. Bf4 {Very active pieces, Rae1 is coming, Black can resign basically.} Nhf8 {Only move.} 20. Re2 $18 {[%cal Gf4d6,Ge7d6,Gf5d6] The evaluation is around +2.}) 16. Rd1 $5 {is a very interesting move. We stop Rc6.} (16. Re1 {Black is in time.} Rc6 $13 {Still compensation for White, but not more.}) 16... d4 {Very likely this move will be played, so that Rc6 is possible, and now we play} (16... Rc6 {hangs d5.} 17. Rxd5 Re6 18. Rd1 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4] With equal material, we are very happy to play this position.}) 17. Re1 $1 {Again Rc6 is not possible.} Kh8 $1 {Only move.} (17... b5 {Black starts counterplay but} 18. e6 $18 {Bf4 also, all is winning.}) (17... Rc6 {runs into} 18. N3xd4 $18) 18. Qc4 {I like this move, we control a lot of squares.} Nb8 {[%cal Gb7d5] From a theoretical point of view, only this is interesting, to play Bd5.} (18... Bc6 {[%cal Gb6b5] is logical, but not the best.} 19. b4 b5 20. Qd3 $14 {It is tricky to hold onto to the pawn center (+0.60).}) 19. e6 {But now White has a fantastic idea:} Bd5 20. Qxd5 $3 Qxd5 21. Nxe7 Qh5 {[%csl Rf7] Only move, Black needs to defend f7 pawn.} 22. Ne5 {[%csl Rh5] But the queen can be also in danger!} Rce8 {Only move.} 23. g4 Qxe5 {Only move.} (23... Qxh4 $4 {At least N7g6, but} 24. exf7 $18 {is even stronger.}) 24. Ng6+ {Best move.} (24. Rxe5 $6 Rxe7 $13 {Black is absolutely fine, they will regain the pawn on e6.}) 24... fxg6 25. Rxe5 $14 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gg4g5] Objectively, Black's position is holdable, but practically, Black is at least worse.} *

