{[%evp 0,19,19,19,22,6,6,6,6,-7,2,0,-2,13,30,19,8,8,17,17,18,18]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 (6... a5 $5 {It's a new variation, recently played by many strong players. We will continue with} 7. Qc2 Nc6 8. a3 dxc4 9. Qxc4 a4 10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Bf4 {And Alexey will analyze it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) 7. Qc2 b6 8. Rd1 {We need to play Rd1, that's why 7...b6 is a completely different variation compared to 7...Nbd7.} (8. Nbd2 {This was good against 7...Nbd7, but against 7...b6 is not great because Black can play} c5 $1 $132 {And his position is immediately very good.}) 8... Nbd7 {[%csl Yc8] This is a tricky move because Black still has not committed to his Bc8 development.} (8... Ba6 {Interesting concrete move. We can play now} 9. Ne5 $5 {[%csl Rb8] White the idea to stop Black's development. We'll discuss it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) (8... Bb7 {[%csl Yb7] Now that Black's bishop is already on b7, we can go for} 9. Nc3 Nbd7 (9... dxc4 {not dangerous because of} 10. Ne5 $14 {and we are slightly better.}) 10. b3 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our idea. We prepare e4, and let's see how Black will continue. We'll discuss this in "Position 2" of this Unit.} ({we don't play} 10. e4 {because of} dxc4 {Where there are a lot of high-level games, and Black's position is absolutely fine.})) 9. b3 {[%cal Ya7a5] We start with b3, and we'll analyze this in "Position 3" of this Unit.} (9. Nc3 {is not good now because Black can play} Ba6 $1 $11 {[%csl Ga6]}) (9. Nbd2 {[%csl Yd1] once again, this is nothing because of} Bb7 {[%csl Gd1]} 10. e4 dxc4 11. Nxc4 c5 $132) 9... Ba6 {Now that Black's bishop is on a6, we will play} (9... Bb7 10. Nc3 {Transposes to 8...Bb7.}) (9... a5 $5 {As we will see, this move has a very hidden positional idea.}) 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Ya8c8,Yc6c5] Black can try here Rc8 or c5.} *

