{[%evp 0,55,19,23,23,1,1,10,13,-21,-1,2,16,2,38,17,12,0,11,12,18,24,18,32,6,7,14,28,29,-2,-50,-64,-16,-37,-13,-14,-28,-41,15,-17,18,-2,13,5,51,53,66,66,45,55,26,4,2,-7,86,70,88,53]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Qc2 b6 8. Rd1 Nbd7 {We will the conclude with the Nbd7 tricky move order. Now it is important to not confuse with the 8...Bb7 line.} 9. b3 {[%cal Ya7a5,Yc8a6] This is my recommendation.} (9. Nc3 {[%csl Yc8] The bishop is not commited yet to b7 and it can go to a6 in one tempo.} Ba6 $11 {Black is absolutely fine.}) (9. Nbd2 {We shouldn't play this move also, because after} Bb7 10. e4 {[%csl Gd1] We transpose to the previous Unit, but our rook is on d1, and this position is very topical nowadays, Black is fine after} dxc4 11. Nxc4 c5 $11) 9... Ba6 (9... a5 {I don't think it is so important for Black to spend a tempo before playing Ba6.} 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {[%csl Ya5] is the best, only 20 games, but a5 may be useful for a hidden idea.} (10... Ba6 {is the most common continuation, but after} 11. e4 {Black has problems.} Rc8 {was tried by Karjakin, I don't really know the idea.} 12. e5 $146 {Although it is a novelty, it is a very normal move.} Ne8 13. Nf1 c5 {looks necessary.} 14. dxc5 {We can take it, all typical moves.} Bxc5 15. cxd5 Bd4 {doesn't win material, we can play} 16. Qb1 $1 Bxa1 17. Ng5 $1 {Fantastic idea.} g6 18. dxe6 $18) (10... a4 $6 {is not good, because we can simply take it.} 11. bxa4 $14 {Even if Black will regain a4 at some moment, we can press on the b6 pawn, press on the queenside.}) 11. e4 {You can play e4 like everybody.} (11. Bb2 $5 {If you are scared that Black knows everything, you can play this to get a game.} c5 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Rac1 Rc8 14. Qb1 $14 {This was the game Mareco-Boyer, 2023, for sure White is slightly better, for sure Black cannot force a draw.}) 11... dxe4 {Now it is a strong idea, even if usually it is not.} (11... Qb8 {was played in Bogner-Tari, I wanted to share one thing.} 12. e5 Ne8 13. cxd5 $1 {is better.} (13. Nf1 {The game continued like this, but after} Nc7 {[%cal Yc4d5,Yc7d5] Now it is not easy to capture on d5, because of Nxd5.} 14. cxd5 Nxd5 $132) 13... cxd5 14. Nf1 $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h2,Gh2g4,Gc1g5,Yf3g5] We have seen similar positions, good prospects for an attack on the kingside.}) (11... Rc8 {Also not great.} 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nf1 c5 {Typical stuff happens.} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 {looks unpleasant for Black.} (14... Nxc5 15. Ne3 $14 {Pressure on d5.}) (14... Rxc5 {Rxc5 is Rxc5.} 15. Qd3 Rc7 16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Ne3 {We put pressure, pressure, pressure.} Bb7 18. Bb2 $14) 15. Ng5 g6 16. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg2b7]}) (11... a4 {is the most played, but White has a very interesting position after} 12. Rb1 axb3 13. axb3 $14 {Typically slightly better.}) 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 {should be played.} (12... c5 $2 {Not c5, because after} 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Ng5 {White captures the bishop on b7 in Maghsoodloo-Bluebaum, 2022 and is tactically winning after} Bxg5 15. Bxb7 Ra7 16. dxc5 $1 {White won material and the game.} Rxb7 17. c6 Rc7 18. Rxd7 Rxd7 19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. cxd7 $18) 13. Qxe4 Ra7 $1 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7b7,Gc1f4] That's why a5 might be useful. Still, if your opponent knows it, White can still play after} (13... Nf6 $6 14. Qe2 $16) 14. Qe2 c5 15. Bb2 {Even here it is a game.} a4 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. bxa4 (17. Ne5 Bxg2 $11 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7d7] The rook needs to stay to protect d7.}) 17... Qc7 (17... Rxa4 $4 {Impossible due to} 18. Ne5 $18 {White wins material and the game.}) 18. Rab1 {Now only one good move for Black.} Bf6 $1 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Ne5 {We can play a slightly prefferable position after} Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Rxa4 22. Rb5 {But it is almost equal, for example:} Rfa8 23. Rdb1 h6 24. Rb7 Rxa2 {If Black plays engine moves, it should be able to equalize.} 25. Qe3 Qd6 26. Rxf7 Rb8 $1 27. Rxb8+ Qxb8 $13 {Still slightly more pleasant for White, but most likely a draw.}) (9... Bb7 {Of course, after this move, we can transpose.} 10. Nc3 {was seen under 8...Bb7.}) 10. Nbd2 c5 {This is the best move for sure.} (10... Rc8 {is the most common move, but is also not fantastic.} 11. e4 c5 {Most played move.} (11... Bb7 {This is obviously good for us.} 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nf1 $16 {Typical position, and Black lost a tempo.}) (11... dxe4 {This is not the same position as with the rook on a7, now we have a nice advantage.} 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 b5 {is Black's idea.} (13... Nf6 14. Qe1 $16 {[%csl Ye1,Re2][%cal Ya6e2] Typical advantage, on e1 the queen is safer and not under a pin.}) 14. Qc2 {We retreat to defend the pawn.} bxc4 15. bxc4 c5 {Best move, and now we are better in different ways.} (15... Qa5 $2 {Most common move, 18 out 28 games, but Black's position is terrible.} 16. Bd2 Qa3 17. Rab1 {The evaluation is +2.} Rb8 18. Rb3 $18 {Domination.}) 16. Ne5 {was played in the game Gajewski-Babula.} (16. d5 {White is better also here, like in the game Jussupow-Markos.} exd5 17. cxd5 $146 {Taking on d5 with the rook is also possible, but I prefer this.}) 16... Nxe5 $146 {is the best for the engine, but Black needs to be ready to play down a pawn after} (16... cxd4 17. Rxd4 Nxe5 18. Rxd8 Rfxd8 {Black doesn't have enough compensation.} 19. Qa4 $146 {was stronger than what happened in the game.} Bxc4 20. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Gg2b7] looks very bad for Black.}) 17. dxe5 Qc7 18. Qa4 Bb7 19. Qxa7 Bxg2 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Kxg2 $16 {I don't know how many players are ready to play this endgame.}) 12. e5 {is my main recommendation, I like it more.} (12. exd5 $5 {is also possible.} exd5 13. Nf1 {It seems that move by move it is not easy to equalize for Black.} cxd4 14. Nxd4 b5 {There were some games also, like Harikrishna-Vocaturo.} 15. Ne3 bxc4 16. Ndf5 $5 $36 {was maybe even stronger. A lot of pressure.} (16. Nxd5 {is how the game continued, Harikrishna won.})) 12... Ne8 13. dxc5 Bxc5 (13... bxc5 {[%csl Yc8][%cal Rc8c2] The rook is not working.} 14. h4 $40 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gg2h3] We can create threats on the kingside.}) 14. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gc1b2]} Be7 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc8c2] The queen can be a target.} 15. Qb1 $146 Nc7 16. Bb2 $14 {Just slightly better for White.}) (10... b5 {was played in some games, but it is a bad move.} 11. c5 b4 {[%csl Ya6] Black needs this move, to activate the bishop.} 12. Re1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2e4] Sometimes we have e4 ideas.} Bb5 13. a4 {is even stronger.} (13. e4 {Usually it is a good move, but now the bishop is well placed after} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 a5 $132 {[%csl Gb5] The bishop is strong on b5, defending c6. Still, White is slightly better.}) 13... bxa3 (13... Ba6 14. e4 $16 {[%csl Rc6] Now we can play e4, and it is not the same, because c6 is a weakness.}) 14. Nb1 $5 {is the idea, to play either Nxa3 or Nc3, and was played by GM Kunin.} Ne4 15. Nxa3 {This looks very good for White.} Ba6 16. Be3 $16 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gf3e5,Gf3d2,Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Ge3c5] Even stronger, that's why b5 is not a good move.} (16. Nd2 {possible.})) 11. e4 dxc4 (11... Rc8 {transposes to 10...Rc8.}) 12. e5 $1 {Very important, only 18 games out of 100 knew this.} (12. Nxc4 $5 {If you just want a positional game, this can be an alternative.} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Rc8 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nf5 {is also possible.} (15. Qb2 $5 {Mysterious move.}) 15... b5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Rxd5 bxc4 18. Qe2 {You can check what is this.}) 12... Nd5 13. bxc4 {This variation is good for Black, but is played only in email games.} Nb4 14. Qe4 {looks fantastic for White.} Qc7 $1 {But this is a very strong idea for Black, the point is:} (14... cxd4 15. Nxd4 {is just slightly better for White.} Nc5 16. Qe3 Bb7 17. Bxb7 Nxb7 18. Ba3 $36 {We have beautiful pieces.}) 15. d5 exd5 16. cxd5 {If I told you that White is winning, many would believe for sure, but Black is saving the position after the only move} f5 $1 {And we can't maintain the center.} 17. Qf4 Nxd5 18. Qa4 Bb7 19. Nc4 Rad8 {Only one over the board happened here out of 5 games.} 20. Qb3 {was played only in email games and is the best move.} (20. Ng5 $4 {Kantor blundered immediately.} Nc3 $19 {[%cal Ra4b3,Gc3e2] Black won in Kantor-Doric, 2021.}) 20... b5 $1 {is only move for Black. Now you see why it is only played in correspondece.} (20... f4 {was played in one game, but White is better after} 21. Bb2 $16) 21. Nd6 c4 {The most accurate probably.} (21... Bxd6 22. Rxd5 {looks very interesting.} (22. exd6 {can also be tried.} Qxd6 23. Qxb5 $44 {Compensation is guaranteed 100%, advantage - I don't think so if Black plays accurate.}) 22... c4 23. exd6 Qc6 {Some concrete line.} 24. Ne5 cxb3 25. Nxc6 Bxc6 26. axb3 Bxd5 27. Bxd5+ Kh8 28. Bf4 $44 {Fantastic compensation, engine will hold, but also engine says that White is slightly slightly better.}) 22. Qxb5 {Now forced moves.} Nc3 23. Qxb7 Bxd6 24. Qxc7 Bxc7 25. Re1 {Over the board looks like advantage, 2 bishops in an endgame, but move by move Black can somehow hold.} Nc5 26. Bg5 Rc8 {is probably the best, but not an easy one.} (26... Bb6 {Even in a correspondence game, Black didn't play the best move.} 27. Bf1 Nd3 28. Rec1 $16 {was a fantastic move, and White was better.}) 27. Rac1 N5e4 28. Bf1 {Now one more move.} Ba5 $1 29. Bd2 $11 {Still, maybe some play is left, after all we are not down in material, but it is an equal endgame; I repeat that this is only played in correspondence, nobody dares to enter such wild complications, I would say that it is an incidental line.} *

