{[%evp 0,33,23,30,30,12,16,12,6,-23,5,-14,11,10,10,-3,32,30,25,22,22,21,18,27,27,27,27,27,34,33,48,27,27,33,48,40]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c5 {This move is not popular, but it's a very logical move, and we need to know what to do against it.} 8. dxc5 {My recommendation.} ({if we play} 8. Qxc4 {then after} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {Black can play the important move} e5 $1 $11 {[%cal Yb8c6,Yc8e6] And his position is absolutely fine. Nc6-Be6 next.}) (8. Rd1 {Looks interesting, but Black has the following tactical idea, which is worth to mention:} Nc6 $1 9. dxc5 Nb4 $1 {Typical idea.} 10. Qa4 Nfd5 $13 {[%cal Gc8d7] Bd7 next, and Black is at least fine.}) 8... Bxc5 {This is, of course, Black's most normal move, but other ideas have also been tried.} (8... Nc6 9. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] We want to take on c4 with the knight.} ({not} 9. Rd1 {because it would transpose in 8.Rd1 and Black is fine after} Nb4 $1) 9... Bxc5 10. Nxc4 $14 {Black's position is unpleasant, for example:} Qe7 {is Black's most common continuation.} 11. Nfe5 $1 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 {[%csl Rc8] it's difficult for Black to develop the bishop on c8, and after} Qc7 {We can play the important move} 13. Be3 $1 Bd6 14. Qxc7 Bxc7 15. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] We have a typical better Catalan endgame. Why? Because our bishop on g2 is much stronger than Black's bishop on c8. If you like to play the Catalan, then you need to like playing these endgames because this is the dream scenario for every Catalan player.}) (8... Qa5 {Strange move. Black wants to capture on c5 with the queen, but the queen will be misplaced on c5:} 9. Nbd2 Qxc5 10. Nxc4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1e3] Be3 next, and we will win some important tempi.} b5 {looks critical, and now White is better only after} 11. Ne1 $1 $146 (11. Ng5 {was played in Nakamura-Nepomniatchi 2024} Nc6 $11 {Black was OK.}) 11... Nd5 (11... Nc6 $4 {it's a terrible move now, because of} 12. Na5 $1 $18 {[%csl Yc2][%cal Ye1c2] And our knight on e1 protects our queen on c2.}) 12. Ne3 $16 {Very difficult position for Black.}) 9. Qxc4 Qe7 $1 {For sure the best. Strangely enough, it's not so easy to find a big advantage here.} (9... Be7 10. Nc3 {White has a typical advantage:} Nc6 11. Rd1 Qa5 12. Bd2 {[%csl Ra5]} Qh5 13. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh5]}) (9... Nbd7 {Passive move.} 10. Nc3 {[%csl Rd7] The knight on d7 is not great, because it's not easy to play b6-Bb7.} (10. Qc2 $5 $146 {[%cal Gb1c3] Also deserves attention. Our queen on c2 is not a target, and we can continue with Nc3 next.} Qe7 11. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Ya2a3,Yb2b4,Yc1b2] Black cannot play b6, and our next moves could be a3-b4-Bb2.}) 10... Qe7 11. Qh4 h6 {Black's wait bishop c1 moves} (11... b6 $2 12. Nd4 $18) 12. g4 $5 Nd5 13. g5 $36 {Looks interesting, at least.}) 10. Rd1 $5 {This is my recommendation, and 10.Rd1 has been played only once, so we can call it an "almost novelty" :)} (10. Ne5 {possible, but Black has a concrete solution:} Bd6 11. Nd3 e5 $1 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Qh4 {looks fantastic, but} Rd8 {not only move, but a good one} 14. Nb5 Nbd7 15. Be3 Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c4] Rc4 is Black's idea.} 16. Rfc1 Bg4 $13 {[%csl Rh4] Very unclear. Our queen on h4 is misplaced.}) (10. Nc3 b6 $1 {looks risky, but Black's best.} (10... a6 11. Bg5 Nbd7 12. Ne4 b5 13. Qc1 Bb7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Rd1 Rfd8 17. Qe3 $14 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7] White is better without any better. Next plan could be Ne1, change bishops, Nf4-Nh5 and mate :)}) 11. Bg5 Nbd7 $1 $146 {This move is a novelty, but I was not able to find ideas for White here.} (11... Bb7 $6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Ne4 $16 {White is better.})) 10... b6 $1 $146 {Once again, this is Black's strongest continuation. Now, I offer you two continuations, and you can choose according to your style.} (10... Nc6 $6 {[%csl Rc8] This is a normal-looking move, but it's not good. Why? Black's priority is to solve the problem of his bishop on c8.} 11. Bg5 Bb6 12. Nbd2 e5 (12... h6 13. Bh4 $16 {[%cal Rg7g5,Gf3g5] If Black plays g5, we are ready to sacrifice a piece by playing Nxg5.}) 13. Ne4 Be6 14. Qa4 $14) (10... Bd7 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gd7c6] Black prepares Rc8-Bc6, but he is not in time because of} 11. Ne5 $1 Rc8 {[%csl Rc4]} 12. Qh4 (12. Qb3 $5) 12... Bc6 $1 {only move} (12... Be8 $2 13. Bg5 $18 {Winning position for White.}) 13. Nxc6 Nxc6 14. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1c1,Gd2e1] We have a long-term advantage. We can continue with Bd2-Be1-Rac1, and be happy about our pair of bishops.}) 11. Bg5 {This is the solid option.} (11. Nc3 {Natural move, but I don't like it.} Bb7 12. Na4 Bd6 13. Bg5 Nc6 $11) (11. b4 $5 {This is the ambitious option. Of course, it's more risky than 11.Bg5, but it's also more interesting:} Ba6 (11... Bd6 $4 12. Ne1 Nd5 13. Bb2 $18 {[%csl Yd6,Yg7][%cal Ge2e4,Yc4d4,Yb1c3]}) (11... Bxb4 12. Nd4 Ba6 13. Qb3 {transposes in 11...Ba6.}) 12. Qb3 Bxb4 {necessary move.} (12... Bd6 $4 13. Nd4 Bb7 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. Nxe6 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6]}) 13. Nd4 Nd5 14. e4 (14. h4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14... Nf6 15. e5 Nd5 16. Nf5 $5 Qc5 $1 $13 {only move. If you want, you can analyze this position, which looks very interesting, but if Black finds all the best moves, it might be a draw.}) 11... Bb7 (11... Ba6 $2 {not good here because of} 12. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 13. Qe4 $16 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ge4a8]}) 12. Bxf6 $5 {This is my idea. It looks a bit strange to give up on the pair of bishops, but our priority is to stop Black's development.} (12. Nc3 Nbd7 $11 {Black is just fine.}) 12... Qxf6 13. Nc3 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rb8d7] Black doesn't have Nd7.} Na6 (13... Rc8 14. Ne4 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Nc6 16. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Gc6] playable. Rad1-h4-e3. If Black's pawn were on b7, it would be complitely equal, but with pawn on b6 some chances.}) 14. Nd4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd4c6]} Bxd4 16. Qxd4 {[%csl Ra6,Gc3,Yc6]} Qxd4 17. Rxd4 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Yc3,Gc6] I won a very similar endgame many years ago in the Aeroflot Open :) White has an initiative because our knight is better, and Black's key c6 square is weak.} *

