{[%evp 0,45,25,15,32,9,9,25,12,-6,16,6,10,14,5,-20,21,19,10,17,10,11,8,2,33,24,16,0,0,-1,44,27,23,25,21,14,23,-26,0,7,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-115]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6 {This move has a very solid reputation.} 8. a4 $5 {This is my recommendation. I don't want to say that 8.a4 is stronger than 8.Qxc4, but there are much fewer games, and it's easier to surprise our opponent.} (8. Qxc4 {Almost always, White automatically captures on c4. It's not a bad move, but there are so many games here that it will be difficult to find new ideas.} b5 9. Qc2 Bb7 {We can follow the important game So-Mamedyarov, Candidates 2018.} 10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. Nc3 Qb6 12. Ne5 Rfd8 13. Be3 Nd5 14. Nxd5 cxd5 $11 {Black's position was absolutely fine.}) (8. Nbd2 {I am not so sure about this move.} b5 9. b3 cxb3 10. Nxb3 {In the mainline 7...a6, we will see similar positions, but here Black's pawn could go on a5 in one move:} a5 $1 {Black is fine. A sample line could be:} 11. Rd1 Nbd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Qxc6 Bd7 15. Qb7 Rb8 16. Qa7 Ra8 17. Qb7 Rb8 $11 {With a draw by repetition.}) 8... b6 {This is Black's most normal continuation and also the most common one. His priority is to develop the c8 bishop.} (8... Nbd7 {of course, Black can play moves like this one, but after} 9. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl Rc8] We just have a better position from a strategic perspective.}) (8... a5 9. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Rc8][%cal Gb1c3,Yb8a6,Ya6b4,Yb7b6,Yc8a6] Doesn't look great for Black. Why? Because he did not solve the problem of his bishop on c8. A logical plan for him could be Na6-Nb4-b6-Ba6.} Na6 10. Rd1 $5 Nb4 11. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Rb7b6,Ge5c6] We stop b6.} Nd7 12. Nc3 $14 {Looks unpleasant for Black.}) 9. Na3 $5 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ga3c4] My idea is to capture on c4 with the knight.} (9. Qxc4 {was tried by GM Chigaev, but after} Ba6 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. Rd1 {his opponent, GM Esipenko, played Na6, but} Qc8 $1 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] Is a strong typical move. Black will play c5 next, and his position is absolutely fine.}) 9... Bb7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black prepares c5.} (9... Bxa3 $2 {This is, obviously, very bad.} 10. Rxa3 $16) 10. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8,Rc6c5] we stop c5.} (10. Nxc4 $6 {Gives nothing because of} c5 $1 $11 {and Black's position is absolutely fine.}) 10... Qc8 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is Black's best move, in my opinion. Why? Because he prepares c6-c5.} (10... Bxa3 $2 {was played by GM Timofeev, but I don't know why. Bxa3 is almost always a bad move.} 11. Rxa3 Nbd7 {Goryachkina-Timofeev, 2023. Here, White played 12.Qxc4, but once again I want to offer} 12. Nd2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4] If possible, we always prefer to capture on c4 with the knight. White has a very serious advantage.}) (10... Nbd7 {[%cal Gc6c5] This is another way to prepare c6-c5, but now we can try:} 11. Ne5 $5 Qc8 12. Naxc4 c5 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 {Maletin-Timofeev, 2018. Now, White did not find the beautiful resource:} 14. Bg5 $1 $146 f6 (14... Bxg5 $6 {looks risky:} 15. Nd6 Qc7 16. Nxb7 Rab8 17. dxc5 bxc5 (17... Nxc5 $2 18. b4 Na6 19. Qxc7 Nxc7 20. Rd7 $16 {White has a seriously better endgame.}) 18. Qb3 $16 {[%cal Gb3b5,Ya4a5,Ya5a6] Qb5, or a5-a6 next.}) 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Be3 $14 {[%csl Re6] Black played f7-f6, and one day, his weak e6 square could make the difference.}) 11. Bg5 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation.} (11. Nxc4 {was played in Ponkratov-Esipenko, 2023, but Black was fine after} c5 $1 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $11) 11... Nbd7 (11... c5 $6 {is dubious because of} 12. dxc5 Qxc5 $4 (12... bxc5 {bxc5 is already a concession.} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nxc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5]}) 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Ng5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rh7][%cal Gg2b7,Gc2h7] typical tactical idea.}) 12. Nxc4 c5 $1 {This is the best moment for Black to play c5. We are already very far from the official theory, but Black's position is strategically good. For this reason, I want to offer you a concrete idea:} (12... h6 $6 {if Black spends another tempo, then it might be too late for c6-c5 in the future:} 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is ready for c5.} 14. a5 $1 {Not so easy to play for Black.} c5 {is his best continuation, according to the engine} 15. axb6 Be4 16. Qc1 {maybe Black has good compensation, but who knows.} Qb7 17. bxa7 Rxa7 18. Rxa7 Qxa7 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. e3 $14 {[%csl Gb2] Black needs to work to bring home the desired draw.}) 13. dxc5 Bxc5 (13... bxc5 $14 {After bxc5 we can always hope to be slightly better because of the structure.}) 14. Rac1 Bd5 {According to the engine, the position is equal, but I have found the following idea:} 15. Nce5 $5 h6 $1 {The best, according to the engine.} (15... Bxf2+ {human move, in my opinion.} 16. Kxf2 Qxc2 17. Rxc2 Ne4+ 18. Ke3 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Nxg5 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Rxd5 $14 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ge5c6] We have chances in this endgame. Why? Because our king is already in the center, and our knight will have the good c6 square.}) 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. e4 $5 Bb7 {only move, and now we can play} (17... hxg5 $2 18. exd5 $18) 18. Bxh6 $5 {This is my idea.} gxh6 19. Qd2 {[%csl Rd7,Rh6][%cal Gd2d7,Gd2h6] We attack both the knight and the h6 pawn.} Rd8 20. Qxh6 Nf8 21. Ne5 Rxd1+ $1 {only move.} 22. Rxd1 Qe8 $1 {another only move.} 23. Rd3 $5 $13 {We can try to play this position. For sure, we have compensation, and Black needs to be precise. In the worst case, we will make a draw by repetition.} ({we can always make a draw with} 23. Qg5+ Kh7 24. Qf4 Kg8 25. Qg5+ $11) *

