{[%evp 0,33,38,20,35,12,15,18,15,-6,10,6,14,15,7,-12,0,-16,23,19,19,19,25,19,34,15,59,-8,15,-30,-27,-43,23,23,18,9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b6 8. Bg5 Nd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {Bb7 is a normal move, but the good thing for us is that it's not so concrete.} 11. Nxc4 Nd7 {Black prepares c7-c5.} (11... c5 $2 {was played by Mamedyarov, but it's premature:} 12. dxc5 Qxc5 (12... Rc8 13. cxb6 Nxb6 14. Nfd2 $1 $16 {White just has an extra pawn.}) 13. Ng5 $1 g6 14. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Yd6] One of our knights will land on d6.}) 12. a3 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4,Rd5b4] We stop Nb4 and we are ready for e4.} N5f6 {Probably Black's best continuation.} (12... c5 13. e4 $1 N5f6 14. e5 Nd5 {Here, Donchenko played Nd6, but Nd6 is not always necessary. I prefer} 15. Rfe1 $5 {[%cal Ra8c8,Gc4d6] Black can never play Rc8 because of Nd6. As Smyslov taught me, the threat is stronger than its execution.} Ba6 16. Qa4 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 Rac8 18. Rac1 Rc7 19. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Yh2h4] We have a good bishop, and we can play a long game. Maybe h2-h4 will be our next move.}) 13. b4 $1 {We make it more difficult to play c7-c5.} c5 $146 {looks logical.} (13... Rfc8 {Percivaldi-Diermair, 2017.} 14. Nfe5 $1 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 c5 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. b5 $1 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qb7+ 19. Nc6 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb5,Gc6][%cal Ga3a4] a4 next, and White is better.}) (13... Be4 {Engine move.} 14. Qb2 c5 {Without c5, Black's position is difficult to play} 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. b5 $14 {[%csl Gb5] The engine will hold, but for a human, this is unpleasant.}) 14. Nfe5 $5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxe5 (15... cxd4 $4 {huge blunder} 16. Nc6 Qe8 17. Nd6 $1 $18 {[%csl Re8] Suddenly, Black lost his queen :).}) 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. b5 $14 {White is better. We can conclude by saying that 10...Bb7 is a bit passive, and Black is not in time to fully-equalize.} *

