{[%evp 0,27,21,18,27,6,6,28,6,-2,5,-2,-2,21,-6,0,3,13,-3,11,49,35,76,29,124,113,90,107,107,107]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 (8... Bb7 {This move is the cause of headache for many theoreticians, but I know that there are many players who are happy to face it. Why? Because Black usually plays positions with pawn down, where if you check with the engine, the engine is optimistic saying it is a draw, but over the board, Black sometimes doesn't achieve the draw.} 9. axb5 a6 10. bxa6 {This is the most principled continuation. Now, Black should try to prove his compensation for the pawn.} (10. Nc3 {This is the kind of line you play for one game.} axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 Bd5 {And you can try to find something new, for one or two games. Black is fine in more than one way and in the best case, White achieves a +0.20 advantage, which is not huge. So I decided it is not practical.}) 10... Nxa6 11. Qxc4 {[%csl Gb2,Rc7,Gd4] So we have an extra pawn, but Black has activity and the play is really move by move.} Bd5 {[%cal Yc4d3,Yc4c2,Ga6b4]} 12. Qc3 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ra6b4] This is the only challenging move. The queen is sidestepping Black's gain of a tempo based on ...Nb4. The following sequence is pretty forced} c5 {The best move.} (12... Ne4 $6 {Is not so good, because we have the e3 square for our queen.} 13. Qe3 $1 {We will check it in "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 13. Be3 (13. Bf4 {This was played by Carlsen, and it is a one game idea. Black is fine in more than one way, so you need to invest a lot of work.} Ne4 14. Qc1 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxf2 $5 {Even this tactic is possible.} (15... Nb4 {was played by Saric against Rapport, and I couldn't find anything.}) (15... Nec5 $6 {was Radjabov's choice, but it is not a good move.}) 16. Rxf2 {Now forced simplifications.} Bxg2 17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Kxg2 Nb4 19. Rxa8 Qxa8+ 20. Rf3 Nd5 $11 {Black is fine.}) 13... Ne4 {[%cal Rc3e3] Now it is a good move, no more Qe3.} 14. Qe1 (14. Qc1 {I don't like.} cxd4 $11) 14... Nb4 (14... Qb6 $6 {was played in one game, but now} 15. Qc1 $1 cxd4 16. Bxd4 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gb1c3] And the tempo and the extra pawn, makes a big difference.}) 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Nc3 {We are down to 26 games, 18 continued with Nxc3 and 8 with Nc2.} Nxc3 (16... Nc2 {Is, in my opinion, less precise because we can play} 17. Nxd5 $1 {And we will discuss it in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 17. bxc3 (17. Qxc3 c4 $44 {Black has positional compensation.}) 17... Nc2 {This is Black's best continuation, and we will discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 9. Nfd2 {This is the most interesting line, in my opinion.} (9. Ne5 {Is White's most common and concrete try. We will discuss about it separately.}) 9... Nd5 {Nowadays, everybody plays Nd5.} (9... b3 {normal move, but very rare and it's unlikely you will face it. If Black plays it, then you will just have a playable position. We'll check it in "Position 4" of this Unit.}) (9... c6 {This move is not so common nowadays, because after} 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 {[%csl Rc5] Black has problems with the queen, and we play for domination. We will discuss it in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) 10. Nxc4 c5 {without c5, our position is just better.} (10... Ba6 $2 11. Rd1 $16 {clear advantage}) (10... Nc6 $2 11. e3 $16 {clear advantage.}) 11. dxc5 {Black has two options: Bxc5 or Ba6.} Ba6 {Black's most common continuation.} (11... Bxc5 {less common, but it became a very serious engine-style line.} 12. e4 Nb6 {necessary} 13. Ncd2 $1 {White's best try. We will see in "Position 6" of this Unit that Black can play 11...Bxc5 only if he remembers an endless amount of concrete computer variations.}) 12. Ne3 Nd7 $1 {Only move.} 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. c6 {This leads to very complicated and sharp positions. We will discuss it in "Position 7" of this Unit.} *

