{[%evp 0,52,27,27,27,16,7,16,16,0,8,8,15,15,17,-3,31,31,43,43,37,37,37,37,37,35,37,37,37,30,30,15,15,15,12,0,7,28,13,8,9,4,45,43,80,27,43,63,69,69,70,71,72,62,82]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 {Recently, the move} Bb7 9. axb5 a6 10. bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qxc4 Bd5 12. Qc3 Ne4 $6 {This could already be our chance, and it was played also by strong players like Niemann, Caruana, Sadwhani, Paravyan etc.} 13. Qe3 $5 {[%csl Ge3] is an extra option, that is very interesting.} (13. Qe1 {You can transpose first of all.} c5 (13... Nb4 $6 {is unpleasant after} 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Nc3 $14)) 13... c5 {is logical.} (13... Nb4 {is not great.} 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Nc3 Bb7 {Black shouldn't give away the bishop pair.} (15... c5 16. Nxd5 $16 {Two bishops and extra pawn.}) 16. Ne1 {It's not clear what to play with Black.} Nxc3 17. bxc3 Bxg2 18. Nxg2 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4] Pawn up and improved structure.}) 14. Nc3 {Now, Black should simplify.} cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 $16 {White is better.} Nc5 $6 {This is Black's most common continuation, but it only makes things worse:} 18. Ba3 $1 Qd5+ 19. Qf3 {Also Nf3 was an option.} Qxf3+ 20. Kxf3 {This endgame is by far not a draw. For example:} Rfc8 21. Bxc5 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Bxc5 23. Ke4 {Extra pawn and king in the center.} Bxd4 $2 24. Kxd4 $18 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gc4c5] The endgame is already winning for White.} *

