{[%evp 0,52,27,27,27,16,7,16,16,0,8,8,15,15,17,-3,31,31,43,43,37,37,37,37,37,35,37,37,37,30,30,15,15,15,12,0,7,28,13,8,9,4,45,43,80,27,43,63,69,69,70,71,72,62,82]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 Bb7 9. axb5 a6 10. bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qxc4 Bd5 12. Qc3 c5 13. Be3 Ne4 14. Qe1 Nb4 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Nc3 Nxc3 {Black should probably start with this move before playing ...Nc2.} 17. bxc3 (17. Qxc3 c4 $44 {Black has positional compensation.}) 17... Nc2 {The most logical and straightforward continuation.} 18. Qd2 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 cxd4 20. cxd4 {[%cal Yf3e1,Yd5g2,Ye1g2,Yf8d8,Ye7f6] So we reach the key position of our variation. Out of 15 games, White won 4, so almost 1 out 3 times White converted the extra pawn. Our plan is to trade the bishops, so naturally Black has to stop it, by pressuring d4.} Rd8 (20... Bf6 {is probably the best move.} 21. Qf4 {[%cal Ye2e3] After e2-e3 and h2-h4, he can consider exchanging the bishops with Ne1.} (21. Ne1 $2 {We are not in time to defend the pawn.} Bxg2 22. Nxg2 Rd8 $11 {[%csl Yd4]}) 21... Qb8 $1 {Black insists on exchanging queens. After such an exchange, White's winning chances will be considerably reduced.} (21... Rc8 {was played in the game Andreikin-Naroditsky.} 22. Rb1 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Gb1b8,Ge2e3,Gf3e1] Activating the rook and planning to exchange the bishops by means of Ne1.}) ({A typical position arises after} 21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Qb8 {Once again, White should refrain from exchanging queens and play} 23. Qe4 $14 {Again, we have the familiar type of position. Black still needs to prove the draw.}) 22. Qg4 {This move is slightly more precise from a practical point of view and the best try.} ({is playable as well but after} 22. Qxb8 Rxb8 23. e3 {[%cal Gf3e1] We miss one tempo.} (23. Rd1 $5 {is also interesting.}) 23... Bxf3 $1 24. Bxf3 g6 25. Ra1 $11 {[%cal Yg8g7,Ya1a7,Yd4d5,Ye6d5,Yf3d5,Yb8f8] With passive defence, we have chances, but with a rook on e7 it will not be easy.}) (22. Ne5 {is possible, but very difficult to win.} Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Rd8 $11 {99% draw I would say.}) 22... g6 23. e3 h5 24. Qf4 {Some non standard engame, but still, not easy to win after} (24. Qh3 {[%csl Rh3] Black doesn't need to anyhting, the queen is misplaced.}) 24... Qxf4 25. gxf4 Bxf3 26. Bxf3 Rd8 $14 {The most likely result is a draw, but we keep playing on. However, to conclude, even if Black 1)decides to enter this line; 2)plays the best moves until Nxc3; 3)knows all the small positional details; 4)enters the correct endgame, Black can still lose :) And each step of the way, as we have seen together, is very unlikely to happen, even the strongest players in the world commit mistakes and lose such endgames.}) (20... h6 {was played in Kezin-Remizov.} 21. Ne1 $1 {is our idea.} Bxg2 22. Nxg2 $14 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ge3f4,Ge2e3] It is a very long game, White can have fun.}) 21. Qf4 {Our idea is to defend the pawn.} (21. Ne1 $2 {We are not in time.} Bxg2 22. Nxg2 Bf6 $11 {d4 falls.}) 21... Bf6 ({After} 21... Bxf3 22. Bxf3 Qb8 23. Qe4 $14 {White enjoys a risk-free edge.}) (21... h6 22. e3 (22. Ne1 {doesn't work for concrete reasons.} Bxg2 23. Nxg2 Bg5 24. Qg4 f5 $11 {[%csl Rd4]}) 22... Bd6 (22... Bf6 {We can start with h4 also.} 23. Ne1 {But this is the easiest.} Bxg2 24. Nxg2 $14 {[%cal Ya8d5,Ye6e5,Yd4e5] We are happy.}) 23. Qh4 Bb4 {was played by Nepo, but I don't like this idea.} 24. Qg4 {[%cal Gf3h4] preparing Nh4 on the next move.} (24. Ne1 $2 Bxe1 $1 {is the point.} 25. Bxd5 Bxf2+ $11) 24... Bxf3 {[%csl Yg6,Rh6,Yh7][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] When Black sees that they can't prevent the exchange of bishops anymore they go for this instead.} 25. Bxf3 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] But concretely it is not so good here, because the move h6 is a weakness. 1-0 (33) So,W (2776)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2773) Bucharest Superbet Classic 2nd 2022 (4)}) (21... Qb8 22. Qxb8 Rxb8 23. Ne5) 22. e3 {[%cal Gf3e1]} Bxf3 {This is the best.} (22... h6 {was played by Niemann, but it is bad for 2 reasons.} 23. h4 {played by Ding is also very good, because whenever Black takes on f3, it will not be equal anymore.} (23. Ne1 {We can trade the bishops.} Bxg2 24. Nxg2 $14) 23... Rc8 {was tried in the game, White maneuvered and won eventually.} (23... Bxf3 24. Bxf3 {[%csl Yh6]} Qb8 25. Qe4 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5] So as you see, ...h6 is a very big positional mistake.}) 24. Ne1 Re8 25. Bxd5 Qxd5 26. Qf3 $14 {Probably Black should keep the queens now, but it is another story. We definitely have the advantage.} Qc4 (26... Qxf3 27. Nxf3 $16 {We have higher chances.}) 27. Qe4 {1-0 (51) Ding,L (2745)-Niemann,H (2711) FIDE World Rapid Team Almaty 2024 (3.7)}) 23. Bxf3 {We try to keep the queens for as long as possible.} Qb8 $1 {is important.} 24. Qe4 {Here Black needs to find the best move again.} Qc7 {seemingly normal move, but after} (24... g6 $1 {is the best defence, Black achieves the desired structure after} 25. h4 h5 $14 {[%csl Ye6,Yf7,Yg6,Yh5][%cal Gh4h5] Probably this is the second best endgame Black can achieve, but we can still try on, we have the queens on the board.}) 25. h4 $1 {White is seriously better.} g6 {[%cal Yh7h5]} (25... h6 26. h5 $16 {[%csl Rg8,Yh7][%cal Gf3e2,Ge2d3] It is very dangerous, that's why it is never a good idea to enter this positions with a pawn on h6.}) 26. h5 $1 {We are in time to push h5.} Kg7 27. Kg2 {Santos played the next sequence of the game very nicely.} Rb8 28. Rh1 Rb2 29. h6+ $1 Kf8 30. Ra1 Rb8 31. Ra6 Rd8 32. Rc6 $16 {The game continued and White won in the end. 1-0 (40) Santos Latasa,J (2675)-Mekhitarian,K (2542) Olympiad-44 Chennai 2022 (3.3)} *

