{[%evp 0,50,21,18,27,6,6,6,6,1,-2,4,21,-6,0,-5,27,40,15,26,26,12,45,49,46,47,39,39,39,23,-5,-32,-32,-30,-44,-38,-33,-25,0,-2,25,43,26,25,30,6,27,70,108,108,73,107,88]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 9. Ne5 {This is White's most concrete variation and although it's not our main recommendation, it's worth to know its current state of theory.} Qxd4 $1 {This is Black's idea.} (9... Nd5 {also possible, but then Ne5 was a good move for us.} 10. Nd2 $1 c3 11. Nb3 cxb2 12. Bxb2 $14 {[%cal Gf1c1] We don't only have fantastic compensation, but also a good advantage.}) 10. Bxa8 {If we play 9:Ne5, we should the go for the critical variation.} Qxe5 11. Bf4 $1 {Very important move; without it, we are worse. The point is that Black's queen doesn't have a fantastic square.} Qh5 $1 {Black's best and only move.} (11... Qa5 $2 12. Nd2 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4] Nxc4 will come with tempo.}) (11... Qc5 $2 12. Nd2 Ba6 13. Be3 Qh5 14. Bf3 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Qxg4 16. f3 Qh5 17. Nxc4 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) 12. Bf3 Ng4 13. Bxg4 Qxg4 14. Qxc4 $1 (14. Nd2 $6 {has also been tried, but after} e5 $1 15. Bxe5 Ba6 $36 {According to the engine, Black already had the initiative.}) 14... e5 $1 {Necessary move. In general, in the 9.Ne5 it's a memorization challenge, so you can just remember all the moves, without even understanding what's going on. But don't forget that Black can do the same!} (14... Ba6 $2 {Would be a big mistake because after} 15. Qxc7 Bf6 16. Re1 Bxb2 17. Ra2 $18 {White's position is winning.}) 15. Qxc7 exf4 16. Qxe7 fxg3 17. Nd2 $1 {Very important move, but everybody knows it nowadays :) This is a very young variation; the first game was played in 2021, until 4 years ago nobody knew anything about this position.} ({After the natural} 17. hxg3 $4 Nc6 $19 {Black's position is already winning.}) 17... gxh2+ {This is the most precise move, in my opinion.} (17... Be6 $4 18. hxg3 Nc6 19. Qd6 $18 {Now White's position is winning.}) (17... gxf2+ {Possible move, but probably not the best:} 18. Kxf2 Qd4+ 19. Qe3 Qxb2 20. Qf4 $1 {[%cal Rb2f6] Strong move, White stops Qf6. Do you think that this is Grand Master level preparation? You are wrong. 20.Qf4 was played two times, by a 1900 and a 1800 players.} Nc6 21. Rfd1 $14 {White is preferable, but the game continues.}) (17... Nc6 18. Qe4 gxf2+ (18... gxh2+ 19. Kh1 Qd7 20. Rad1 $1 $146 Re8 21. Qf4 Rxe2 {necessary} 22. Ne4 Qe7 23. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 $14 {Move-by-move, Black might hold, but it seems that it's White who is playing for the advantage.}) 19. Kxf2 Qd7 20. Nf3 Re8 21. Qc4 Bb7 22. Rad1 Qe7 23. Kg1 h6 24. Rd3 $1 $14 {It seems that White is slightly better.}) 18. Kh1 Qf4 $1 {Black's only move not to be worse.} (18... Be6 $2 {Black forgot the theory, and lost immediately in the game Matlakov-Oparin, 2021:} 19. f3 Qd4 20. Ne4 Qxb2 21. Rab1 $18) (18... Nc6 $2 {Natural but bad.} 19. Qd6 $1 $16) (18... Nd7 $2 19. f3 $1 $18) 19. e3 Qf5 {I think that Black has full compensation. I tried to check a bit deeper:} 20. f3 $5 $146 Nc6 21. Qe4 Qf6 {Difficult to understand which could be Blacks' problem in the future.} 22. Rac1 Ne5 {[%csl Rh1] Our king is open, so all can happen in a real game.} 23. Rc5 Ng6 24. Qxb4 Ba6 25. Rf2 Qe7 $13 {Unclear, and the game is open for all three results. In conclusion, I think that 9.Ne5 is not interesting for us, because we cannot play a normal chess game, and if our opponents know the best move, our position is also practically risky.} *

