{[%evp 0,37,36,12,25,7,6,6,6,-12,9,-6,-6,-6,18,-4,20,18,17,28,18,7,0,20,35,0,0,0,19,12,16,15,17,15,12,20,33,-9,0,4]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 9. Nfd2 {This is the most interesting line, in my opinion.} c6 {This move was common in the past, but after the game Grischuk-Nakamura 2019, it disappeared from practice.} 10. Nxc4 Qxd4 {Necessary move for Black.} (10... Ba6 $2 {Of course, if Black doesn't take on d4 we can just play} 11. Rd1 $16 {And we are much better positionally.}) 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 {[%csl Rc5] Black's problem is that the queen doesn't have fantastic squares.} Qh5 {only move} (12... Qf5 $2 13. Qxf5 exf5 14. Nbd2 $16 {[%cal Yf6d5,Ye3d4,Gc4a5,Ga1c1] White has very big compensation. Na5-Rfc1. All our pieces have very good squares.}) 13. Nbd2 {Now Black tried different moves, but 13...Ng4 is the best.} Ng4 $1 (13... e5 $2 {[%cal Yc8h3] Black's idea is Bh3, but after} 14. Ne4 $1 Ng4 (14... Bh3 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bc5 $18 {We have domination.}) 15. h4 $16 {Terrible position for Black.}) (13... Ba6 $2 {Just a bad move.} 14. Bf3 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Qxg4 16. f3 Qh5 17. Ne4 $16 {domination.}) 14. Nf3 {[%cal Ge3d4] We want to play Bd4, so Black must capture on e3.} (14. Nf1 $5 {deserves attention.}) 14... Nxe3 15. Nxe3 {It's absolutely clear that White has very good compensation and initiative.} a5 {Is Black's best move, according to the engine.} 16. Nd4 Ba6 (16... Qc5 $6 17. Qe4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga1c1] Black's queen on c5 stays bad. We will play Rac1 next, with a big advantage.}) 17. Rac1 Ra7 $1 {This is stronger than 17...Rc8, but the general picture doesn't change: we have huge compensation, and it's very difficult to play for Black.} (17... Rc8 $6 {was played by Nakamura, but after} 18. Bf3 Qg6 19. Be4 Qh5 20. Kg2 $5 {Not White's only move, but a good move.} Ra7 21. h4 g6 22. f4 $16 {[%csl Rh5] Black's queen on h5 is very bad. White has the advantage. Let's see some more moves from the game Grischuk-Nakamura:} Qh6 23. Nb3 (23. Ng4 $1 Qg7 24. Ne5 $16 {was even stronger.}) 23... Kh8 24. Bd3 Bb7 25. Nc4 c5+ 26. Be4 Ba6 27. Nbxa5 Qf8 28. Bf3 $16 {After this game, no strong player has ever repeated the 9...c6 line.}) 18. Qe4 $5 {My idea. It's more concrete than 18.h4.} (18. h4 $5 $146 {deserves attention.} Rc7 19. Bf3 Qg6 20. Be4 Qh5 21. Kg2 $14 {Grischuk style. Pressure, pressure and pressure.} (21. Bd3 $5 Bxd3 22. Rxd3 $14)) 18... Bc5 $1 {not easy to play Bc5 without preparation} (18... Rc7 {human move, but after} 19. Bf3 {[%cal Rh5e5] no Qe5 move.} Qg6 20. Qe5 $14 {[%csl Ra5] Black's position is shaky. We can always take on a5.}) 19. h4 $5 $14 {Even if Black finds the best move 18...Bc5, we are still slightly better and the game continues.} *

