{[%evp 0,60,27,12,17,6,6,6,16,-12,-6,-6,-6,17,-4,0,17,28,46,28,33,33,41,41,115,107,105,101,105,132,132,98,132,109,136,104,134,126,126,125,106,128,125,114,116,65,61,-44,-46,7,66,-27,-29,-52,-52,-52,-8,-79,35,44,65,-13,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 b5 8. a4 b4 9. Nfd2 Nd5 10. Nxc4 c5 11. dxc5 Ba6 {Black's most common continuation.} 12. Ne3 $1 {White's only interesting continuation.} (12. Rd1 {has been tried, but after} Nd7 $11 {Black is just fine.}) (12. e4 {normal move} Nf6 13. Rd1 Nbd7 14. c6 {looks very good, but after} Rc8 15. e5 Nd5 $11 {Black has no problems.}) 12... Nd7 $1 {Only move.} 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. c6 (14. Bxd5 Rc8 $44 {very good compensation for Black}) 14... Rc8 15. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gc6c7,Yf4c7] Our bishop on f4 will support the c6-c7 move.} (15. Rd1 {is a possible try, but I don't believe in it:} Ne5 16. Rxd5 Rxc6 17. Qd1 (17. Nc3 Qc7 $11) 17... Rd6 18. Rxd6 Bxd6 19. Nd2 $132 {Maybe some tries are possible, but also visually it's clear that Black has good compensation.}) 15... Nc5 16. Rd1 (16. c7 {Not interesting:} Qd7 17. Nd2 g5 $1 18. Be5 Qe6 $11 {just fine for Black.}) 16... d4 $1 (16... Bc4 {After this move, it's our chance to play for the advantage:} 17. Nd2 Bxe2 18. Nb3 $1 Bxd1 19. Rxd1 $36 {White has fantastic initiative.}) 17. h4 {[%cal Yg7g5] useful move against g5} (17. Be5 {Is a concrete move, but after} d3 18. exd3 Bxd3 19. Qd2 Ba6 $1 {only move} 20. Qc2 Bd3 21. Qc1 Re8 $1 {only move} 22. Nd2 Be2 $11 {Black is fine. I have tried to analyze it, but I was not able to find any serious idea.}) 17... h6 $1 {Black's best continuation, because it's very important for him to have g7-g5 in the future.} (17... Re8 $2 {Many players did this mistake:} 18. Nd2 $1 Bxe2 19. c7 Qd7 20. Rdc1 $16 {[%csl Gc7] Our pawn is very strong, and no serious idea for Black.} Nd3 $4 21. Bc6 $1 $18) 18. Be5 {This is my offer. It's a novelty, and my idea is not to beat the engine, but to create serious problems for a human opponent.} (18. c7 $6 Qd7 19. Nd2 Bxe2 20. Rdc1 Nd3 $15 {compared to Re8, no Bc6}) (18. Bf3 {The most logical way, but it leads to an equal position} Re8 19. Nd2 d3 {only move} (19... Bf8 $4 20. Nb3 $18 {Nguyen-Deac, 2020.}) 20. exd3 Bxd3 21. Qc1 Bf8 $3 {Another only move. If Black forgets it, we win immediately} 22. Re1 Qf6 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. c7 Rc8 25. Qe1 Bd6 26. Bxd6 Qxd6 27. Rc1 Rxc7 28. Qe8+ Kh7 29. Qe3 Bf5 {Exist some opinion that this position is slightly better for White, but that's not true.} 30. a5 Ne6 $11 {Firouzja-Nihal, 2021.}) 18... d3 19. exd3 Bxd3 20. Qd2 {first we go on d2 because maybe he forgets about Ba6 :)} Ba6 $1 21. Qc2 Bd3 22. Qc1 Re8 23. Na3 $5 {This is my recommendation, and it's a move that will for sure surprise your opponent.} bxa3 {only move} (23... Bf8 $2 {Maybe your opponent will be scared to take on a3 :)} 24. Nc4 f6 25. Qf4 g5 $1 (25... fxe5 26. Nxe5 $18) 26. hxg5 hxg5 27. Qe3 $1 fxe5 28. Be4 Qd4 {only move} 29. Bxd3 $16 {positional advantage}) 24. b4 {It's difficult to play from the Black's side because 99% chance that he will not be prepared for it!} Qb6 {probably the best.} (24... Nb3 25. Qxa3 Nxa1 26. Bxa1 {From a human view, it looks like White is better, so I doubt that your opponent will play 24...Nb3.} Qd6 27. Rxd3 Qxb4 28. Qa2 $5 $36 {[%cal Gg2d5,Gd3f3] looks more interesting than Qxc5. If somebody would tell me that White's position is winning, I would believe}) (24... Na6 25. c7 Nxc7 26. Qxa3 Bxb4 27. Qxb4 Rxe5 28. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Rd3,Gg2][%cal Yd1d3] We will take on d3, and we have practical chances because our bishop could be stronger than Black's knight in the future.}) 25. Bxg7 $5 {our opponent will be in shock probably} Kxg7 26. bxc5 Qa6 {very human move} (26... Qxc5 27. Rxd3 Qxc1+ 28. Rxc1 $11 {during the game, it's not clear for Black if this is equal.}) (26... Bxc5 $2 27. Rxd3 Bxf2+ 28. Kh2 $16) 27. Rxa3 Bf5 {he will relax a bit, but after} 28. Rd6 {I don't know what he will think} Bxd6 29. cxd6 {Without computer, Black can lose very quickly} Qa5 $1 {only move. Now, we can try many moves, but we only have practical chances, because the position is objectively equal:} 30. Qa1+ $5 (30. Rc3 $5) (30. Kh2 $5 Re1 31. Qc4 Rd1 32. Qf4 Be6 33. Bf3 Rd2 34. Bg2 Rd1 $11) 30... Kg8 $1 (30... Kh7 $2 31. Qf6 $18) (30... f6 31. Qd4 $36) 31. Qd4 Qe5 32. Qxe5 Rxe5 33. d7 Bxd7 34. cxd7 Rd8 35. Bc6 $11 *

