{[%evp 0,25,28,29,38,1,6,6,18,-23,2,2,1,0,3,-9,6,-39,-36,-34,-27,-27,-17,-28,-28,-28,-28,-20]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 $5 {This is an intriguing and underexplored idea, with only about 150 games in the database. This line has been a favorite of the creative GM Daniil Dubov, who used it several times, including in his match against Magnus Carlsen.} b5 $1 {This is undoubtedly Black's best continuation and, if you think about it, the only drawback of our move 8.Rd1 compared to the mainline 8.a4.} (8... Bd7 {[%csl Gd1] This is Black’s strongest continuation in the mainline with 8.a4, but here it’s questionable because, against Bd7, White’s Rd1 proves far more effective than the move a4.} 9. Ne5 $1 Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Qxc4 $16 {[%csl Gd1,Yd4] Thanks to the move 8.Rd1, our pawn on d4 is not hanging.}) (8... Nbd7 {Black can play many moves like this, and they are all not critical. We will speak about Nbd7 and other sidelines when analyzing the "Position 1" of this Unit.}) 9. Ne5 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gg2a8] We activate our bishop, and Black now has two logical continuations.} Nd5 {This is Black’s most common continuation. Unlike the alternative 9...c6, Black aims to keep the long diagonal open for the bishop, hoping that once Bb7 is played, it will be more active without the c7-c6 move blocking its potential.} (9... c6 {This was Magnus Calrsen's choice. We will play the typical} 10. b3 $5 cxb3 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Yd1][%cal Gg2c6,Ge5c6,Gc2c6,Ga1a6] We sacrificed a pawn, but we have fantastic pieces. We will discuss this in depth in "Position 2" of this Unit.}) 10. b3 {This is the typical idea of the 8.Rd1 variation.} cxb3 {by far the most common continuation.} (10... Bb7 $5 {This move is very rare in practice, but it's possible according to the engine. After} 11. bxc4 Nb4 $1 {Black may be able to hold if he will find all the best moves. We will discuss it in "Position 3" of this Unit.}) 11. axb3 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Ya1a6] Of course, we recapture with the pawn, at least because our a1 rook is now working.} Bb7 {Standard move. Difficult to imagine that Black will play something else.} 12. Ba3 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Yc5,Ye7] Without Ba3, our compensation becomes uncertain. Why is Ba3 a strong move? -By exchanging the dark-squared bishops, we can gain control over the critical c5 square. -Our bishop lacks a productive square, while Black’s dark-squares bishop could become significantly more effective than ours.} ({For example, I don't like a move like} 12. Bb2 {because of:} Nb4 13. Qc3 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qd5+ {Black has no problems, and maybe he already has some advantage.}) 12... Bxa3 {Most natural and popular move.} (12... Bd6 {[%cal Ra3d6,Gc7d6] This is a tricky move because Black does not allow the bishop's exchange. Of course, Bxd6 is not good because of cxd6.} 13. Nd3 {We play this standard idea and we have a very strong compensation for the pawn. We will consider this in "Position 5" of this Unit.}) (12... a5 {While not theoretically critical, this move has been tested by strong GMs like Yu and Vocaturo, so we’ll explore it in 'Position 6' of this Unit.}) {after} 13. Nxa3 $44 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ge5d3,Gd3c5] We have a very interesting positional compensation. I could even go further by saying that we have a positional initiative! We will consider it in "Position 4" of this Unit.} *

