{[%evp 0,31,20,20,20,18,15,15,15,-7,8,19,5,2,2,2,0,-39,24,37,41,38,38,8,5,11,21,-89,-98,-78,-38,-43,19,-36]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 {b7-b5 is, of course, Black's most critical continuation. But what happens if he plays another move?} Nbd7 {This is probably Black's best alternative to the main move 8...b5.} (8... Bd7 $2 {Why Bd7 is bad now, but it was Black's most common continuation in the 8.a4 variation? because after} 9. Ne5 $1 (9. Qxc4 Bc6 $132 {Would be more or less normal for Black.}) 9... Bc6 ({if} 9... Nc6 {White is just better after} 10. Qxc4 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 12. Nc3 c6 13. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Rd7,Ge4]}) 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Qxc4 $16 {Imagine this position with our pawn on a4 and our rook still on f1. Black would just play Qxd4, which would solve all his problems. You can now see with 8.Rd1 is so much more useful than 8.a4.} Qd7 (11... Nd5 12. Nc3 Nb6 13. Qd3 Bf6 14. e3 $18 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Yg2b7] White has a huge positional advantage. The position might already be winning for us.}) 12. Nc3 Rfd8 13. e3 $16 {Positionally better for White. Two bishops, good center, good development, and no concrete plan for Black.}) (8... Nc6 {This move is always bad:} 9. Qxc4 $14 {[%csl Rc8] We take on c4, and Black doesn't have any active plan. Please notice that the problem of the bishop on c8 still exists. Let's see a game played by the guru of the 8.Rd1 variation, GM Dubov.} Nb4 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black prepares b5-Bb7.} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc4c1] very good move. Without mentioning all the obvious benefits of this move, I want to make you notice that White's queen will have the c1 square.} b5 11. Qc1 (11. Qb3 {was also good.}) 11... Bb7 12. Nbd2 {[%cal Rc7c5] It's very difficult for Black to execute c7-c5.} h6 {This is a very bad move because, anyway, White's idea was to take on f6 sooner or later.} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. a3 Nd5 15. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb3c5] The knight goes to the ideal c5 square.} Nb6 16. Nc5 $16 {I don't think that we need to check the rest of the game, because White already has a very obvious big advantage.}) 9. Ne5 {This is the most concrete and ambitious move.} (9. Nfd2 $5 {This move is also interesting, but Black can achieve a more or less normal position if he plays the best moves:} Nb6 10. Nxc4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 {[%cal Gc1f4]} e5 $1 {If not for this move, we would have continued with Bf4, and our position would have been better.} 12. Nc3 (12. d5 Bd6 $132 {is normal for Black.}) 12... Be6 $1 {Black provokes d5.} 13. d5 Bf5 $132 {There are no games in this position, you can probably still play with White, but Black's position is acceptable.}) (9. a4 $5 {Objectively, this is not White's best, but it's also a very good move, and you can use it if you want to avoid forced variations. Let's see the game Deac-Nisipeanu, 2021.} Nd5 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Gd5b4] Black knight wants to go on b4.} 10. Nbd2 (10. Bd2 $5 $14 {was an interesting idea, with the intention to capture on b4 if Black plays Nb4.}) 10... b6 {Nisipeanu is a strong Grand Master but not an engine, so he played b6 with the idea of developing his bishop on b7. Objectively, this move is bad, and you can observe how easy it is for Black to end up in a worse position even by playing logical moves.} (10... b5 $1 {was possible, according to the engine. After} 11. axb5 Bb7 $1 $11 {The position is equal.}) 11. Nxc4 Bb7 12. e4 $1 {was the correct continuation.} (12. Nfe5 $6 {Was played in the game, but after} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Nb4 14. Qb3 Bd5 $1 $11 {Black's position was absolutely fine.}) 12... Nb4 13. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White has a strong center, and Black does not have any counterplay. White is better.}) 9... Nxe5 (9... c5 $6 {[%csl Gd1,Rd8] Black is not ready for this move. Why? Because our rook is on d1 and his queen on d8 :).} 10. dxc5 Qc7 11. Nxc4 Bxc5 12. Be3 $5 Bxe3 13. Nxe3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] Black can choose if to take on c2 or if to avoid the endgame, but anyway we have a typical Catalan advantage thanks to our good bishop on g2, and Black's passive bishop on c8.}) 10. dxe5 Nd5 $1 {The best.} (10... Nd7 $2 {Very serious mistake:} 11. Nd2 $1 Nxe5 12. Nxc4 Nd7 13. Bf4 $18 {[%csl Gc2,Gc4,Rc8,Gd1,Rd8,Gf4,Gg2] White's intiative is too strong.}) 11. Na3 $1 {[%csl Yc2][%cal Ga3c2,Ge2e4] We protect our queen, and we are now ready for e4.} ({Black's idea is that after} 11. e4 $2 {he has} Nb4 $1 $17) 11... Bxa3 $1 {Necessary move.} (11... b5 $2 12. e4) (11... Bd7 12. Nxc4 b5 13. Ne3 c6 {Was played in the game Pantazar-Tallaksen, 2022. Now, White found a very strong idea:} 14. h4 $1 {Very often, when you don't know what to do, h2-h4 is the way.} Qb8 15. Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5] Our idea is Bg5.} h5 {Looks critical because Black wins a pawn.} 16. Nh2 Qxe5 17. Nf3 Qc7 18. e4 $16 {We not only have compensation, but also a very serious advantage thanks to our much more active pieces.}) 12. bxa3 {Black's position is unpleasant, but maybe not absolutely bad.} Qe7 13. Rd4 $5 {[%cal Gd4h4] This might be stronger than Qxc4.} (13. Qxc4 $14 {Is also possible, and enough for a small but pleasant advantage. After all, our pieces are active, and we have two bishops.}) 13... b5 {Black can now defend the pawn, but we start a kingside play:} 14. Rh4 g6 15. Bh6 Bb7 $1 {Necessary move. If we take the exchange, Black will have full compensation, but we can still try} (15... Rd8 $2 {very bad move. White is better after may moves, for example} 16. Qc1 $1 $18 {[%csl Rg7,Rg8][%cal Gh6g5] Bg5 next, and Black is lost because the dark squares around the king are too weak.}) 16. Qd2 $40 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gh6g7,Gh6g5] With a lot of interesting ideas. The engine can hold Black's position, but in a real game, this looks like a very strong attack.} *

