1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 b5 $1 9. Ne5 c6 {Carlsen's choice. After c6, the position is not so complicated, and Carlsen probably wanted to avoid Dubov's preparation.} (9... Ra7 {looks strange, we can play} 10. a4 {and if} c6 {[%csl Ra7] We already have} (10... Bb7 $146 {this is the strongest move for the engine.} 11. axb5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Qd5+ 13. f3 Qxb5 14. e4 $14 {[%csl Rc4] Black is not lost, but our position is obviously better.}) 11. Bxc6 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra7] And Black's rook on a7 is misplaced.}) 10. b3 {only 13 games here.} (10. Nc3 $5 {b3 was not White's only move.}) 10... cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 {The most logical move.} (11... Ra7 {was played in the game Dubov-Inarkiev. Inarkiev is a very strong player, but the position was new for him, and you see how easy it is for Black to make mistakes.} 12. Nc3 $1 $146 {[%csl Ra7][%cal Gc3e4] Our idea is Ne4. For example:} (12. Nxc6 $2 {not good because of} Nxc6 13. Qxc6 Rc7 $17 {And Black is better. Remember: We don't need to rush to capture on c6.}) 12... Qb6 13. Ne4 $14 {White is better because we have a much-improved version of the mainlines.}) 12. Nc3 {Nc3 was played in the match Dubov-Carlsen, and it will be our main move in this file.} (12. Ba3 {was played twice by Dubov, but Ba3 is maybe not so strong against the 9...c6 variation.} Bxa3 $1 $146 {Nobody has played it, but this is Black's strongest option.} (12... Nd5 {This move was played by Anand.} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd2 (14. Nc3 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 14... Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Ge4c5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] This is a typical good situation for White: Our knight can safely land on c5, but we also have h4-Ng5 ideas. Let's check the game Dubov-Anand for understanding.} a5 17. Nc5 Qc7 18. e3 $132 {Timid move, but doesn't weaken the position. Dubov won the game, but it was blitz, and the rest it is not so interesting for us.} ({It was the right moment for} 18. e4 $1 Nb4 19. Qd2 $36 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Ge4e5,Gh2h4] Then White can play e5-h4, with attacking chances against Black's king.})) (12... Nfd7 13. Nd3 $14 {Dubov-Svane, 2022. We can check this game for understanding:} a5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nc3 Rc8 16. Ne4 {[%csl Yc5] White controls the c5 square with all pieces.} (16. e4 $6 {Is not good because of} e5 $1 $11 {and Black is immediately fine.}) (16. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc3b5] This was White's strongest continuation. Our idea is already Nxb5.} Na6 $2 {not possible now, because of} (16... e5 $4 {huge mistake now because of} 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qd8+ Qe8 20. Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rb7]}) (16... Nf6 {is Black's strongest defense, but after} 17. Nc5 Na6 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 19. Rxa5 $14 {it's clear that White is better.}) 17. Rxa5 $16 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Ra6b4] Our queen is on d2, and this means that Black doesn't have the Nb4 idea.}) 16... Na6 $1 {logical move: Black develops a piece and controls the c5 square.} 17. Qd2 {Dubov played Qd2 now, but it's not the same.} (17. Rxa5 $2 {is not possible because of the typical tactical idea} Nb4 $1 $17 {Remember it!}) 17... Nb4 $2 {big mistake.} (17... f5 $1 {was Black's correct continuation. Only after} 18. Nc3 Nb4 $1 $132 {is good, and the position is equal.}) 18. Nxb4 axb4 19. Nc5 $1 Nxc5 20. Qxb4 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Yc5] White will recapture the knight on c5, and Black needs to play with the terrible bishop on b7.}) 13. Nxa3 Nbd7 {I was not able to find a way to get a playable position:} 14. b4 (14. Nxc6 Qb6 $11 {[%csl Ra3] Knight on a3 stays very bad.}) 14... Qb6 {[%cal Ga6a5]} 15. Nd3 a5 $1 $11 {Black is always in time to simplify.}) ({Other unknown moves are also possible, for example:} 12. Bb2 $5 Qc7 (12... Nbd7 $2 13. Nxc6 $16) 13. Nd2 $132 {[%cal Gd1c1] Rc1 next.}) ({or} 12. Bg5 $5 {also deserves attention. If you feel that your opponent is super well-prepared, then you can use one of these unknown moves and just play this typical position.}) 12... Nbd7 {This is probably Black's most logical continuation.} (12... Nd5 $6 {It doesn't make sense now because if Black wanted to play Nd5, then it was better to do it at move 9 when his pawn was still on c7.} 13. Ne4 $14) (12... Qb6 $6 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Yb6c6,Gb8d7] Human move, to defend c6 pawn and Nd7 next.} 13. Ne4 Nbd7 14. Ng5 $1 g6 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Be3 {[%csl Rb6]} Qc7 17. Ne4 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5]} e5 $2 {not possible because of} 18. d5 $18) (12... h6 {was played once in the Dubov-Carlsen match. Black plays a useful-waiting move and wants to see White's idea.} 13. Bf4 $5 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gc2c1,Yf4h6] This is my recommendation. Bf4 is a useful move, and sometimes we have Qc1 ideas where Black's pawn on h6 might become a target.}) (12... Nfd7 13. Ne4 Qc8 14. Nd3 c5 15. Bg5 Bxg5 16. Nd6 Qc7 17. Nxb7 Ra7 18. Ndxc5) 13. Nxd7 $5 {tricky move because Black needs to understand how to recapture.} (13. Ne4 $2 {Dubov-Carlsen, 2021.} Nxe4 $1 (13... Rc8 $2 {was played by Carlsen, but after} 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 (14... Nxd7 15. Bf4 Qb6 16. Bd6 Bxd6 17. Nxd6 Rc7 18. b4 Rd8 19. e4) 15. Nc5 $16 {White would have achieved a huge positional advantage.} Bxc5 16. dxc5 Qc7 17. Bf4 e5 18. Bg5 Nd5 19. e4 Nb4 20. Qc3 f6 (20... a5 21. Bh3) 21. Be3 a5 22. Rd6 Rcd8 23. f4 Bc8 24. f5) 14. Bxe4 Nxe5 $1 15. dxe5 Qc7 $132 {In the best case, we might be able to equalize, and that's why 13.Ne4 is a mistake.}) (13. Bg5 {Possible move. We are following the game Abbasov-Abasov, 2021.} Rc8 (13... h6 $1 {Is Black's strongest move, according to the engine. But it's not easy, because for a human it's much more natural to play Rc8 and defend the c6 pawn.} 14. Bxf6 (14. Bxc6 Qb6 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Ne4 $11) 14... Nxf6 15. Ne4 $44 {We can play in our typical style, and we have for sure compensation and maybe an easier-to-play position.} ({capturing the pawn is not interesting:} 15. Nxc6 Qc7 16. Ne4 $11)) 14. Nxd7 $5 $146 {Do you remember? After 13.Nxd7, Black's strongest recapture was Qxd7, but here it's Nxd7. It's not easy to understand these small details over the board, and that's why White has practical chances.} Nxd7 $1 (14... Qxd7 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Ge4c5] Nc5 next, and White has some advantage.}) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Ne4 Rfd8 {Black plays normal moves. How to continue?} (16... c5 {logical, but risky because of} 17. Ng5 $1 Qxg5 18. Bxb7 Rc7 19. Bxa6 $14 {Some problems for Black.}) 17. h4 $5 $44 {As a rule, when you don't know how to improve your position, h2-h4 is very often a good way. The game continues, and if you are more familiar with the typical ideas of this structure, then you will have more chances than your opponent. This is why I always want to show you many examples, and not just theory, because this is a line for understanding and not for memorization.}) 13... Qxd7 $1 (13... Nxd7 $6 14. Ne4 $14) 14. Bg5 a5 {normal useful move.} (14... Nd5 15. Ne4) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 (15... gxf6 $5 {is another possible recapture, and it's difficult to evaluate all the consequences. But not everybody wants to play like this.} 16. Ne4 Rfc8 17. Nc5 Qc7 18. Qc3 Kg7 19. Nxb7 Qxb7 20. Rxa5) 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5 Qc7 19. Rd6 Rfd8 20. Qd2 $44 {Compensation for sure, maybe some initiative.} *

