{[%evp 0,42,25,26,27,-17,-17,4,0,-26,10,18,-15,-12,-16,0,-2,-21,-21,-40,-42,-42,-9,-3,9,2,2,2,2,2,2,-20,5,0,5,-30,0,0,0,7,-14,-10,-1,15,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 b5 $1 {Black's best continuation.} 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. b3 Bb7 $5 {This is the engine's recommendation, but it has been played in only three games. Why? Because Black has to make a lot of only moves, just trying to make a draw, without the guarantee to achieve it.} 11. bxc4 Nb4 $1 (11... bxc4 $2 {Is a very serious mistake, because after} 12. e4 $1 {White has a huge advantage. For example:} Nb4 (12... Nf6 13. d5 $1 exd5 14. exd5 $18 {[%csl Rb8,Rd8][%cal Ge5c4,Gb1c3] Black's position is objectively lost.}) 13. Qb2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb2b7] We take profit of the position of Black's Bb7.} (13. Qxc4 $6 c5 $132 {Too many exchanges are in the air.}) 13... Qc8 14. Nxc4 $16 {c7-c5 is impossible because of Nb6.}) 12. Qb3 {[%csl Yd1][%cal Gb3d1] This is another try. The good thing about Qb3 is that our d1 rook is protected.} (12. Qc3 {Is one try.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 c5 $1 14. Bb2 {Over the board, this is an absolutely playable position. Only one game was played here, and we can check it.} Bf6 15. Nf3 $5 {This is a better try than Qf3.} (15. Qf3 {Belous-Brown, but Black was fine after} Nd7 16. Nxd7 (16. dxc5 $2 {is impossible because of} Nxe5 $19 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge5f3]}) 16... Qxd7 17. Nc3 cxd4 18. Ne4 Be5 19. e3 $11 {White was not worse, but also not better.}) 15... N4c6 16. cxb5 cxd4 {very close to equality, but maybe White can still play somehow} 17. Qa3 $5 $132 {With few accurate moves, Black will equalize, but I am not sure that every player will find them.}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 {Not easy for Black to play c5 because we protect our rook.} N8c6 {This move was played in the game Arnaudov-Boensh, 2022. Now, I want to suggest} (13... c5 {possible, but I am not sure that is so good:} 14. dxc5 Qc7 15. Bf4 g5 $3 {Only move.} (15... Qxc5 $2 {Human move, but after} 16. Nd2 $16 {White is seriously better because it's not easy for Black to complete the development.}) 16. Qxb4 gxf4 17. gxf4 Nc6 $1 (17... Bxc5 $6 {another human move, but objectively bad:} 18. Qb2 $36 {[%cal Ge5g4]}) 18. Qc3 $14 {For the engine, Black's position is not so bad, but over the board, it is not so clear how to play for Black.}) (13... bxc4 14. Nxc4 {How to play for Black?} N8c6 (14... Qd5+ {looks logical, but after} 15. f3 N8c6 (15... c5 $2 16. a3 N4c6 17. Nc3 $18 {Black is lost.}) 16. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5]}) 15. Bb2 Qd5+ $1 {only now Qd5, because Black's next move will be Na5.} 16. Kg1 Na5 17. Nxa5 Qxa5 18. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rc7] /= Black has played a lot of the engine's best moves, but the game still continues because we have a better structure. Of course, if your opponent will play very well for the next moves, then he can make a draw.}) 14. c5 $1 $146 {Unusual position, and no games here.} Bf6 $1 {Is Black's best continuation.} (14... Nxe5 $4 {not possible because of} 15. dxe5 $18 {[%csl Yb3,Rb4,Yd1,Rd8][%cal Yb3d1] And you can notice how important it is that our rook on d1 is defended by the queen on b3.}) 15. Nf3 {Black can equalize with only moves, but will everybody understand how?} Qd5 $1 16. Qxd5 Nxd5 $1 {we can try} (16... exd5 $2 {bad move} 17. Na3 $14 {[%cal Rb4c2,Ya3c2] We stop Nc2. The position is unusual, but could be better for us.}) 17. a4 $5 {The position looks normal for Black, but playable for White.} h6 $1 {Is the strongest move for the engine, but I cannot fight against an engine.} (17... b4 $2 {is a mistake because of} 18. e4 $16) 18. e4 Ndb4 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Na3 Ra5 $11 {Engine says equal, and we must believe him. 10...Bb7 is a very serious move if you are searching for the truth of the position, but it has been played only three times, and Black needs to make a lot of strong moves just to make a draw. It's impossible for him to analyze all White's possible continuations; that's why I think that in 90% of the cases, you will achieve a game when playing White.} *

