{[%evp 0,35,23,30,18,6,22,22,15,-5,-6,0,0,0,0,0,0,-41,-27,-41,-45,-36,-40,-38,-38,-42,-23,-13,-18,-13,0,4,5,-15,-22,0,0,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 b5 $1 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Ba3 Bxa3 {This is Black's most common continuation.} 13. Nxa3 Nd7 {[%csl Yd8][%cal Yd8b8] Black's best, according to the engine. The queen on d8 is flexible, and it keeps the option of going on b8 later.} (13... f6 $2 {[%csl Re6] Was played in the game Dubov-Steinbuerg, 2020. f6 is a huge mistake, why? Because anyway, our knight's plan was to go on d3, and by playing f6, Black just weakened his pawn.} 14. Nd3 {Black provoked Nd3, that anyway was our idea} Nd7 15. e4 $1 N5b6 16. Nc5 $18 {Black is already lost.}) (13... Nb4 {Black forces the exchange of the bishops.} 14. Qc5 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nd5 (15... Qd5+ 16. Qxd5 Nxd5 17. Nxb5 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7][%cal Ge5d3,Gd1c1] Unpleasant endgame for Black.}) 16. Nxb5 $1 Nd7 $1 {only move} 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Now, we have two possible continuations:} 18. Na3 {This is more interesting because we also keep the knights.} (18. Nc3 Nxc3 19. Qxc3 $14 {/=. Objectively draw, but better structure. You will probably make nine draws and one win from this position.} Rfb8 20. Ra3) 18... Rfb8 19. e4 Nf6 20. Qc2 {For the engine, this is equal, but in a real game, I can easily see White getting something from here. Let's do an experiment: I will play for Black the second-best moves according to the engine. Why the second? Because if he plays all the first moves, then, of course, we can never win.} a5 {Normal move.} 21. Nc4 Qb5 {another very normal move.} 22. Ra3 {[%cal Gf2f3] In future our position could be better. We have the center, we can continue with f3, and we wait for the opponent's mistake.} Rd8 23. f3 Ra6 24. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Ra5] Black is playing well, but step-by-step, we can improve our position, and suddenly, he might face some problems.}) (13... Qe7 {Very human move. It has been played in four games.} 14. Nd3 {we continue with our standard idea.} Nd7 (14... Rc8 {This was played by the young FM Costa. Very probably, this player knew engine's recommendation until some point, but when he started to play on his own, he collapsed under positional pressure:} 15. e4 Nf6 {First small mistake; Nb4 was the best.} 16. Nc5 c6 $6 {Second mistake; Bc6 was the best.} 17. Nb1 {Probably, the White player did not like his knight on a3; that's why I cannot judge his choice of playing Nb1 back.} ({I would have considered} 17. e5 Nd5 18. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Ge4d6] Nd6 next. Very probably, Black will need to sacrifice an exchange for our knight on d6.}) 17... Ra7 {Third mistake; a5 was the best.} 18. e5 $1 $16 {In just three moves, from a 0.00 evaluation, White got a +1,50 advantage without even playing the best moves. This is a very good example that shows that OTB it's much easier to play from White's side this position.}) 15. e4 N5f6 $1 {[%csl Re4] Black counter-attacks the e4 pawn.} (15... Nb4 $4 {not possible because of} 16. Nxb4 Qxb4 17. Qxc7 $18) (15... N5b6 $6 16. Qxc7 $14) 16. Re1 {we protect the pawn} (16. Qxc7 $6 Bxe4 $15) (16. Qe2 c5) 16... Rfc8 {This is Black's most natural move. His idea is c7-c5.} (16... c6 {Looks strange, but now I can show you a new positional idea:} 17. e5 Nd5 18. Bxd5 $5 exd5 {[%csl Rb7] Necessary move, but now Black needs to play with a very bad bishop on b7.} (18... cxd5 $6 {Looks normal, but Black is worse after} 19. Qc7 $1 Rab8 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. Nc2 $16 {domination.} b4) 19. Qc3 $14 {[%cal Ga3c2] Our idea is Nc2.}) 17. b4 $1 {Very important for us to stop the liberatory move c7-c5.} e5 {As c7-c5 is no longer possible, Black tries to execute his second liberatory move: e7-e5.} ({if Black just waits, for example with} 17... h6 {We have compensation after any move} 18. Qb3 $14) 18. Qb3 $5 $146 {[%cal Ga3c2] I like this move. My idea is to prepare Nc2.} (18. dxe5 $2 {not recommendable.} Ng4 19. f4 c5 $15) (18. Qd2 $5 {Interesting move against exd4.} Ne8 (18... exd4 $2 19. e5 Nd5 20. Nc2 $16) 19. Bh3 $132) (18. Qb2 {Concrete idea, but Black is in time to equalize:} exd4 19. e5 Nd5 20. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2d4,Gd4f5]} c5 21. e6 $5 fxe6 22. bxc5 Nxc5 23. Nxc5 Qxc5 24. Nxd4 {looks very interesting, but unfortunately after} Qc3 $1 {Black is in time to exchange queens.} 25. Qxc3 Rxc3 26. Nxe6 Re8 $11 {Don't worry; even here, White is not worse.}) 18... exd4 {looks critical.} 19. e5 Bxg2 20. exf6 $1 (20. Kxg2 $2 Ne8 $17) 20... Qxf6 21. Kxg2 c5 $1 {only move.} 22. bxc5 Nxc5 23. Nxc5 Rxc5 24. Nb1 $11 {Objectively equal, but practically, the draw is not guaranteed for Black. I will go deeper into the position in the video lesson.}) (13... Qd6 {[%cal Gb8d7] Logical move. The idea is to play Nd7 but without allowing Nc6.} 14. Nd3 Nd7 15. e4 Ne7 16. b4 $1 {We have a good center, Black's pieces are passive, and the compensation is guaranteed. We can check the game Belous-Thavandiran, 2017.} Rfd8 (16... Rfc8 17. Qc3) 17. Rac1 (17. Qc3) 17... c6 {[%csl Rb7] First mistake: c6 was not necessary, and now the bishop on b7 is passive.} (17... Rac8 18. Qc3) 18. Qc3 $1 {[%cal Ga3c2] White prepares Nc2.} Qb8 {Second mistake; Qc7 was better.} 19. Nc2 Nc8 {Third mistake; Nc8 is just a bad idea.} 20. Ne3 Ncb6 21. Nc5 Rc8 22. h4 $16 {Once again, in a few moves, Black's 0.00 evaluation became +1,50 for White. Why? Because over the board it's much more difficult to play for Black in this line.}) 14. Nc6 {was played by Dubov, the hero of our 8.Rd1 variation.} (14. Nd3 {also possible, but} Qb8 $1 $146 {Black's queen stays better on b8.} (14... Qe7 {trans in 13..:Qe7.}) 15. e4 N5f6 16. Qe2 $5 (16. Re1 Rd8 {The queen on b8 might support the a5 move (for example a5-Nxb5-Bxe4)} 17. Qc3 a5 $1 {[%csl Yb5,Gb8][%cal Gb8b5]} 18. Nxb5 Bxe4 $15 {[%csl Gb8] This is a good example that shows the potential of Black's queen on b8.}) 16... a5 17. Rdc1 Rc8 18. h4 {[%cal Rc7c5] Black cannot play c5, and it might be playable for us. For example:} h6 19. g4 $5 $13) 14... Bxc6 15. Qxc6 N7b6 {Dubov - Vidit} (15... N7f6 {Was a better move for Black.} 16. Rdc1 $5 (16. e4 Ne7 17. Qc5 c6 {[%cal Gf6d7]} 18. Nc2 a5 $132 {no problem for Black.}) 16... Qd6 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18. e4 Nb4 19. Nc2 Nxc2 20. Rxc2 d5 $11 {Just equal.}) 16. Nc2 $1 $146 {very playable position for White} (16. e4 {Was played by Dubov.} Nb4 17. Qc3 Qe7 18. h4 {As you can see, Dubov improves his position with h2-h4. Once again, we have a good example of how Black's position transformed from 0.00 to lost:} Rfd8 19. h5 h6 20. Bf3 {So far, Black played good moves.} Kf8 $6 {First strange decision. Why Kf8? I cannot understand it, but it shows that it's difficult to play even for a player like Vidit.} 21. Kg2 Rac8 {Second mistake.} 22. Nc2 Nxc2 23. Qxc2 Ra8 $2 {Third mistake: once again, the decisive one:} (23... c5 $1 {Was, of course, necessary.} 24. dxc5 Rxd1 25. Qxd1 Qxc5 26. Rxa6 $14 {Not easy position for Black, but objectively holdable.}) 24. e5 Ra7 25. Qh7 $18 {Dubov-Vidit, 2020.}) 16... Qd6 (16... Ne7 17. Qc3 $14) 17. Qc5 $1 Rfd8 18. Ra5 $14 {[%cal Gd1a1,Gh2h4,Gg2f3,Gg1g2] Black needs to play well. We can improve the position with h4-Bf3-Kg2, eventually Rda1. What is our plan? To wait for Black's mistake. As I have shown you in many examples, very often in a few moves, Black loses by himself; all we need to do is put pressure, pressure, and pressure.} *

