{[%evp 0,43,19,34,29,4,4,1,5,-32,-1,14,2,1,46,-15,-8,-25,-13,-56,-41,-39,-27,-42,-33,-79,-30,-8,-3,-6,9,33,10,12,5,15,15,36,36,35,35,24,41,44,44,40]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 b5 $1 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Ba3 Bd6 {What is the idea of Bd6? Black doesn't want to allow the bishops exchange. Of course, Bxd6 is not good because of cxd6.} 13. Nd3 {What is the idea of Nd3? We are ready for Nc5 or for the e2-e4 plan. Black needs to find a move that works well against both of our ideas.} Nd7 {It was played in the Dubov-Grischuk game, and it looks like Black's most logical move.} (13... Bxa3 {[%csl Gd3] Was played twice. If you think about it, this move transposes to our "Position 4", but we have an extra move Nd3, which is generally useful for us.} 14. Nxa3 Nd7 {Logical move; difficult to suggest something else.} 15. e4 $1 {As always, Dubov shows us the right direction.} (15. Rac1 {Was played in the game Salinas-Pichot, but I don't like this idea:} Qe7 16. Qb2 Rac8 17. Nc5 $6 (17. b4 $1 $132 {Was, of course, necessary, with the idea to stop c7-c5.}) 17... Nxc5 18. Rxc5 Rfd8 19. Rdc1 c6 $132 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Ge6e5] Black is ready for e5, and our knight on a3 is very bad. That's why in Salinas-Pichot, 2023, Black had a very good position and won the game.}) 15... N5f6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] Black attacks our e4 pawn.} 16. Qe2 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Ge2e4] We protect the e4 pawn with the queen.} (16. Re1 {Was played in the game Dubov-Vidit, but it was much stronger to protect the e4 pawn with the queen.} Qb8 $1 {[%csl Gb8][%cal Yb8b5,Ga6a5] Was Black's best plan. What is the idea? To play a6-a5 next, and the queen on b8 indirectly defends b5.} (16... Rc8 $6 17. b4 $1 $14 {White stops c5 and has a better position.})) 16... Qb8 {This was the best against 16.Re1, but here we can start a kingside initiative with} 17. g4 $5 $36 {And the position looks very interesting for us.}) (13... Nc6 $6 {This move looks very strange:} 14. Nc5 Qc8 15. e4 $1 Nde7 {In the game Kaasen-Lin, White played f4, but} 16. d5 $1 {Was much stronger. For example:} exd5 17. exd5 Ne5 18. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 14. Nc5 $5 $146 {This is my recommendation.} (14. e4 {Dubov's choice. It's also interesting, and it leads to a more complicated game compared to my 14.Nc5!? idea.} Bxa3 $1 15. Rxa3 N5f6 (15... Ne7 $5 16. b4 Nc6 {[%csl Rb1] I don't like our knight on b1.} 17. Qc3 e5 18. d5 Nd4 $13) 16. Nd2 Qe7 $2 (16... a5 $1 $132 {Was Black's correct continuation.}) 17. b4 $16 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Ge4] White had a dream position in Dubov-Grischuk, 2022.}) (14. Nd2 {also normal move. For example:} Qe7 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. dxc5 b4 17. Bb2 Qxc5 18. Qxc5 Nxc5 19. Rac1 Nd7 20. Bxd5 {draw, but some trap exists.} exd5 (20... Bxd5 $2 21. e4 Bb7 22. Rxc7 Bc8 23. Nc4 $16) 21. Rxc7 Bc8 {[%cal Rd2c4] No Nc4. for computer it's equal, but this is also playable OTB.} 22. Nf1 Nf6 23. Ne3 Be6 24. Nc2 a5 25. Nd4 $11) 14... Nxc5 {leads to a forced variation:} (14... Bxc5 15. dxc5 Bc6 16. Nc3 $36 {[%csl Gb2,Rd5][%cal Ga3b2] It looks very interesting to us because our bishop on b2 will be very strong.}) 15. dxc5 Be5 16. c6 $1 Bxc6 {only move.} 17. Ra2 {[%cal Gc2c6,Ge2e4] Qxc6 and e4 are serious threats.} b4 (17... Bd7 {also possible, but it's less convincing:} 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 19. Bxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Qe8 21. Nc3 $36 {For the engine, Black has some compensation, but in a real game, it might not be that easy to prove it.}) 18. Qxc6 bxa3 19. Bxd5 (19. e4 $4 Nb4 $1 $19 {Is Black's idea.}) 19... exd5 20. Rxd5 Qf6 $1 {The most precise continuation.} (20... Qe7 21. Nxa3 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] Nc4 next, White is slightly better.}) 21. Qxf6 (21. Qc4 {we can also decide to keep the queens.} Rad8 22. Nxa3 $132 {Now it's equal, but in real life it could become better for White in the future.}) 21... Bxf6 22. Nxa3 $132 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gd5d3] Probably it's a draw, but Black must play well, and we don't have risk} *

