{[%evp 0,46,25,26,27,-11,-12,6,6,-20,14,2,13,-4,7,-13,-4,-21,-21,-39,-45,-40,-38,-23,-23,-23,-2,-2,-6,-6,6,-16,-21,-12,-11,-11,-11,-11,-11,-11,58,58,58,15,33,33,33,33,33]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. Rd1 b5 $1 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. b3 cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Ba3 {We have seen the two most natural moves, Bxa3 and Bd6. But what happens if Black plays another move? Do you think that nobody will play something else? You are wrong, because GMs Yu Yiangy (2700+) and Vocaturo (2600+) played 12...a5.} a5 {[%cal Ge7a3,Yd5b4] What is Black's idea? Bxa3-Nxa3-Nb4 and the pawn on a5 supports the knight on b4.} 13. Bxe7 $1 {In the second time that Dubov faced this variation, he improved by playing 13.Bxe7.} (13. Rc1 {Was tried by Dubov against Yu.} c6 {Was played by Yu. Why do we check this game is 13.Rc1 is not my recommendation? Because it's very important to learn a lot of ideas to improve your understanding of this structure.} (13... Bd6 $1 {is the strongest move for Black, and after the typical} 14. Nd3 {Black has an additional idea:} Na6 $1 $132 {[%csl Ga6] Maybe we still have compensation, but we should be already careful not to end up in a worse position.}) 14. Nd2 $2 {Mistake} (14. Bxe7 $1 {Was necessary, and after} Qxe7 15. Nd2 {White has a game. We will see this exact position in another move order.}) 14... Bxa3 $1 15. Rxa3 b4 16. Raa1 Nc3 {Black's knight on c3 is very strong. GM Dubov made a lot of mistakes, but White's position is still defendable. Of course, now we need to use our compensation to make a draw and not to win, but this shows that even if things go wrong, you can still play.}) 13... Qxe7 14. Rc1 {[%csl Yb1] I like the move Rc1, because the knight on b1 is still flexible, and we can decide later how to develop it.} c6 {Was played by Vocaturo, and it's a normal move. Of course, Black could have played something else, but in this structure it's not so important to know move by move, but it's much more useful to understand the ideas.} 15. Nd2 {Nc3 was also possible, but Nd2 looks interesting.} (15. Nc3 $5 {It was another good possibility. If, in one game, you play 15.Nd2, you can play 15.Nc3 in the next one. As you see, we have a big choice, and it's difficult for Black to study all White's possible moves before the game.}) 15... Nb4 {logical move, and the best according to the engine.} 16. Qc3 Rd8 17. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c5] We are ready to play Nc5.} f6 {Vocaturo plays very well: all the engine's first moves.} (17... Nd7 {is another possibility, but after} 18. Nxd7 Rxd7 19. Nc5 Rdd8 20. e4 $36 {[%cal Yh2h4] Not only we have compensation, but also the initiative. What could be our next move? h2-h4, you already know that this move is very often useful.}) 18. Nd3 Nxd3 19. exd3 $1 {[%csl Ye6,Rf6][%cal Gc1e1,Ge4c5] Very creative move played by Dubov. Usually, it's not a good idea to recapture like this, but here it's an exception because Black has played the move f7-f6, which means that we can play against the e6 pawn on the 'e' file.} b4 {Of course, this is not a huge mistake, but practically, the position becomes unpleasant.} (19... Na6 $1 {It was the strongest move, but Black had to understand that sacrificing the a5 pawn was fine. As you can see, even if your opponent plays very well some moves, like Vocaturo did, very likely sooner or later, he will make a mistake.}) 20. Qc5 $1 Kf8 $1 (20... Qxc5 $2 21. Nxc5 Bc8 22. Rc4 $1 {How do you evaluate the position? Here it's not a debate if our compensation is enough or not, because White's position is already winning.}) 21. Rxa5 (21. Qxe7+ Kxe7 22. Nc5 Bc8 23. Rc4 $36 {Was also fine. Here, Black is not lost because compared to 20..:Qxc5, his king is closer to the center, but White keeps the initiative.}) 21... Qxc5 22. Nxc5 Rxa5 23. Nxb7 Rdd5 $14 {[%cal Yg2d5,Yb7a5] Dubov played Nxa5, but Bxd5 was another interesting choice. Practically, White is pressing in the endgame, and Dubov managed to convert this initiative into a full point. Dubov-Vocaturo, 2015.} *

