{[%evp 0,9,27,27,27,6,6,6,6,-2,-7,-9]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ {This is a very solid option for Black. We could write an endless amount of books about this variation, but we managed to cover all this huge line in just a unit. How is this possible? Because we will go for something fresh where just a very few games have been played.} 5. Nbd2 {Our recommendation. Why? Because it is more fresh, and it leads to a type of position where it's easier for White to play for the full point, in my opinion.} (5. Bd2 {Is White's main move. It leads to a very big theory with more than 20.000 games, and it's extremely difficult for White to find new ideas.}) 5... O-O (5... dxc4 {Black can also take on c4 immediately. After} 6. Bg2 {Very likely the game will transpose into the mainline, but Black has a few alternatives, and we also need to discuss about the move orders. We'll work on it in "Unit 6 part 3".}) 6. Bg2 dxc4 {This is Black's critical continuation.} (6... c6 {In "Unit 6 part 1" we'll cover all Black's sidelines. For example, the move 6...c6 is a very possible move that an unprepared opponent could play against us. Of course, it's not critical, but we still need to know how to face these sidelines.}) (6... b6 {[%csl Rb4] Is Black's solid option. We will play a positional game and we hope to use the misplaced position of Black's Bb4.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. b3 {Is my recommendation, and we'll discuss it in "Unit 6 part 2".}) 7. O-O {My recommendation.} (7. Qc2 {Is by far White's most common continuation.}) 7... b5 8. Ne5 $5 Nd5 9. a3 Be7 10. b3 {This is the critical position of our repertoire against 4...Bb4+. The very good news for us is that it has been reached in just seven games, which means that there is still a lot of space for creativity and new ideas. We'll discuss it in "Unit 6 part 4".} *

