{[%evp 0,37,28,30,32,-14,-14,-14,1,-28,-8,-31,-16,-35,59,28,37,41,38,35,45,43,39,11,-8,56,55,-23,9,-23,36,44,106,114,110,102,103,103,103,116]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 Bb4+ {[%cal Gb1d2,Gc1d2,Gb1c3] The most solid and reliable continuation for Black.} (4... dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Nbd2 $5 {We can play Nbd2 in this move order, cutting a lot of lines.} (6. Bd2 {is the main line, but both a5 and c5 are very serious options.} a5 (6... c5))) 5. Nbd2 {For the reasons mentioned, we recommend this move, which is very practical. In this lesson, we will check all the sidelines.} (5. Nc3 {It is a very strange Nimzo or Ragozin, where White played g3. I think it is not very interesting, although some games have been tried.}) (5. Bd2 {The main move, but it is not our recommendation. The first reason is that you need to study many more lines, the second reason is that after} Be7 {It is very tough to find anything for White.} (5... Bxd2+) (5... a5) (5... Bd6) 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {[%cal Yb8d7,Yc7c6]} c6 8. Qc2 Nbd7 {There are 7000 games here, White cannot find advantage in all the lines.} 9. a4 {Lately has been tried, we also investigated it, but it is nothing.}) 5... O-O (5... dxc4 6. Bg2 {It is likely to transpose after 6...0-0 7.0-0.}) 6. Bg2 {[%cal Yd5c4,Yb7b6] Black's main two options are b6 (the positional line) and dxc4 (the concrete line). We are going to check now the alternatives, but first thing that should be said is that we are not scared of facing them, because a typical Catalan position arises, with little theory, and Black has no chances of killing the game out of the opening, and we are happy to get a game.} c6 {[%csl Rb4] Very natural move, but the main issue is that the bishop on b4 is misplaced.} (6... a5 {is a recent trendy idea, Black tries to play this move in many positions.} 7. O-O a4 (7... Nc6 $6 {can be met with} 8. a3 Be7 9. b3 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ra5a4] Very important, the knight is now completely misplaced.} a4 10. b4 $16 {White is just much better.}) 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rb8c6,Ge5d3] I discovered this move, it was played only once, but it is pretty good. The idea is to stop Nc6 and somewhere Nd3 might be an idea.} (8. Nb1 $5 {[%cal Yb4e7] was my first intention, because we lose two tempi with the knight, but also Black will have to lose one to retreat the bishop to e7, and maybe a5-a4 is not so useful for Black. It is very interesting idea.}) (8. Qc2 {is met with} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Ya4,Yc6] Knight is usually bad on c6, but when a4 is played it is not so bad.} 9. Rd1 (9. a3 {We are not in time to play b3 compared to 7...Nc6} Be7 $132 {[%csl Yb3]}) 9... Be7 {[%cal Gc6b4] Idea is Nb4.} 10. a3 Bd7 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc6a5,Ga5b3] b3 square might be weak in the future.}) 8... c5 {When playing Ne5 in the Catalan, c5 is always an important move to check.} (8... a3 {is logical, but we are not scared to change the structure.} 9. Qc2 axb2 10. Bxb2 {Our pieces are very active.} Be7 11. Rfc1 c6 12. a4 {[%csl Rc8] We can start to play on the queenside, and the c8 bishop is very problematic.} Nbd7 13. Nb3 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5] Already +1 position, it feels like White is playing alone.}) (8... Nbd7 {Nbd7+a4 is not a great combination for Black, but it was played in the only game.} 9. Ndf3 {is the best, I think.} (9. Qc2 {was played in that game, but} c5 $146 {Black is okay.}) 9... Nxe5 (9... c6 $6 {Normal move, but after} 10. c5 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ga2a3,Gb4a5,Gd1a4] Suddenly problems.} a3 11. bxa3 {is the simplest.} Bxa3 12. Qb3 Bxc1 13. Rfxc1 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2] I think it is clear which bishop is better.}) (9... Be7 10. Qc2 c6 {[%csl Ya4,Rd7]} 11. h4 $16 {[%csl Rc8] Typical Alexey Dreev waiting move.} (11. Re1 $5 $16)) 10. dxe5 {is even stronger.} Ne4 11. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf1d1] The knight is not so confident on e4.}) (8... Be7 9. b3 $5 axb3 10. Qxb3 $16 {Very similar to 8...a3, our pieces are very active.}) (8... Nc6 {is another music, we can just} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Nf3 $16 {With this structure, nobody wants to play from the Black side.}) 9. a3 Bxd2 10. Bxd2 cxd4 {looks necessary.} 11. Bb4 {The line gets quite concrete.} Re8 12. cxd5 exd5 {The best recapture, but now Black has an isolated pawn.} (12... Nxd5 13. Qxd4 Nxb4 14. Qxb4 $16 {[%csl Ra4,Rb7,Rc8,Gg2] Development and also the pawns are terribly weak.}) 13. Qxd4 Nc6 14. Nxc6 {We change the structure, but it is still good.} bxc6 15. Rac1 Bd7 16. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Gb4] The bishop is strong on b4, the structure is preferable for White.}) (6... c5 {This is a move that we should be prepared against, because it is not easy to figure out the best continuation without knowing the position.} 7. a3 $1 {The last move by popularity, but the strongest one, I think.} (7. cxd5 {is not interesting.} exd5 $11 {Black is absolutely fine.}) (7. dxc5 {also leads to nothing.} Bxc5 $11 {[%csl Rd2] Black has no problems, and the knight on d2 is now misplaced.}) (7. O-O {is a possible move, but not my recommendation.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {But Black is also quite solid.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qc2 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ga7a5] Dubov tried to play this move, but Black is fine after many moves: e5 or a5.}) 7... Bxd2+ {Black is forced to take.} (7... Ba5 $2 8. dxc5 $16) 8. Qxd2 {[%cal Yc5d4] We want to be able to recapture with the queen on d4.} cxd4 (8... dxc4 {We are not afraid of this move.} 9. dxc5 Na6 10. Qxd8 {We get a typical endgame after} Rxd8 11. c6 {11.Be3 is also possible.} bxc6 12. Ne5 {There are no games here, of course, if Black finds all the best moves, engine should survive, but this is an incidental line, it means that our opponents should not be prepared. For example:} Nc5 $1 13. Bxc6 Nb3 14. Bxa8 Nxa1 15. O-O $14 {It is a game, we can play with two bishops.}) 9. cxd5 {Black should recapture with the queen.} Qxd5 (9... Nxd5 10. b4 $146 {[%cal Gc1b2] Two bishops, very interesting position.}) (9... exd5 {It is not a good isolated pawn, you can recapture both ways.} 10. Qxd4 (10. Nxd4) 10... Re8 11. Qd3 {First defend e2 and then castle.} (11. O-O {doesn't work concretely.} Rxe2 {Black can take it.} 12. Be3 Nc6 $132) 11... Qe7 12. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1] Just a pleasant position, no games here.}) 10. Qxd4 Nc6 {is the best of course.} (10... Qb5 {[%cal Ge1g1] With the idea to prevent castle.} 11. a4 {We can harass the queen.} Qa6 12. b4 {Big problems for Black.} b5 13. axb5 Qxb5 14. Ne5 $18 {It is +2 already.}) (10... Qxd4 $6 {To exchange queens is not great.} 11. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rb8,Rc8,Rf6,Gg2] Catalan endgame, White is slightly better with no effort.}) 11. Qh4 {We fight for more, only 3 games here, so no theory.} (11. Qxd5 {Taking is possible, although Black has a better version.} Nxd5 $132 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5][%cal Yf8d8,Yc8d7,Ya8c8] The knights are already developed. Still it is a playable endgame for White, but we can fight for something more.}) 11... Qb5 12. a4 {is better.} (12. O-O {was played by GM Sivuk, it is interesting, big compensation, but no advantage.} Qxe2 13. Re1 Qb5 $44 {1-0 Sivuk,V (2552)-Diaz Velandia,J (2371) Valencia Cuna op 2021 (3)}) 12... Qa5+ (12... Qa6 {is again met with} 13. b4 $1 b5 14. Bb2 $16 {Black's position is much worse.}) 13. Bd2 $14 {We can castle on the next move, good position for White.}) (6... Nc6 {simply doesn't stay well in this structure, it is not losing or anything, but White can just play.} 7. O-O $14 {No need to check further, you can just play typical moves.}) 7. O-O {Of course, Black is still very solid, and the position was reached in 300 games. It is very likely that people who are not prepared may go for it.} Nbd7 {is the most common move.} (7... b6 {I am following the game Predke-Nesterov.} 8. Qc2 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6f1] is more active.} (8... Bb7 {is also possible of course.} 9. Rd1 Nbd7 10. e4 {Very good move, and now it is a big question. How to play with Black?} Be7 {[%cal Yc6c5] was played in the game Sarana-Gholami.} (10... c5 {[%csl Yb4] It is not easy to play c5 with the bishop on b4.} 11. e5 {At some moment we can even play Nf1 with the idea of a3, the bishop is really misplaced.} Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Rb4] Black needs to think about the bishop.}) (10... Rc8 {So far, Beliavsky is playing very naturally.} 11. e5 {Good move.} Ne8 12. Nf1 Be7 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qe2 {We again have the structure, which typically is very good for White.} Nb8 {[%cal Gb7a6]} 15. Bf4 g6 $2 {is a bad move, but it is not at all easy to play these positions.} (15... Ba6 16. Qd2 $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h2] It is not easy to find counterplay, while White has a clear plan to attack.}) 16. h4 Ng7 17. Ne3 Ba6 18. Qd2 {Sebenik got a crushing position and won.} Nc6 19. Ng4 $18 {1-0 Sebenik,M (2528)-Beliavsky,A (2627) Ptuj op 2015 (9)}) 11. e5 {White can grab more space of course.} (11. b3 {was a timid move by Sarana, now Black can play} c5 $132 {[%cal Ge4e5,Rf6e4] And the position is playable for Black.}) 11... Ne8 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nf1 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h2,Gh2g4,Gc1g5] Typical much better position for White.}) 9. Rd1 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gd1d8] is a very good move, we make it more difficult for Black to play c5.} (9. b3 {I don't think it is a great move, because of} c5 $1 {In this structure you should watch out for this move.} 10. a3 {Nesterov went wrong with 10...Ba5 and Predke won in the end, but} Bxd2 {is the best.} 11. Bxd2 Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Ya8c8] White is slightly slightly better, but the position is completely playable for Black.}) 9... Nbd7 (9... c5 {is another music already.} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nf1 $1 $16 {[%csl Yb4] And the situation is very bad with the bishop on b4.}) (9... Be7 {Improves the bishop, but White has a full extra tempo, so it is quite suspicious.} 10. b3 (10. Z0 c5 {Something like this would be fine for Black.}) 10... c5 11. e4 $16 {We are ready for e4 already.}) 10. e4 {We can check Sarana-Dimitrov game, White played very well.} dxe4 11. Ne5 $1 {Very strong move.} (11. Nxe4 $6 {The important c4 pawn is hanging.} Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bxc4 $15) 11... Bxd2 (11... Rc8 $2 12. Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rc6,Rh7] White has a winning advantage.}) 12. Bxd2 Bb7 13. Bg5 {Sarana put a lot of pressure and after} Qc8 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 15. Qxe4 $16 {White has the pair of bishops and extra space, White won a nice game.1-0 Sarana,A (2685)-Dimitrov,R (2488) Munich Pfingst op-A 1st 2023 (6)}) 8. Qc2 {[%csl Rb4] Once again, the bishop is misplaced, and if Black retreats, White is just tempo up comparing to other lines.} Re8 {Now it is an instructive point.} (8... b6 {is normal move, but White reaches typical middlegame after} 9. e4 Bb7 10. e5 Ne8 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. a3 Be7 13. Re1 $40 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gh2h4,Gc2d1,Gd1g4,Gd2f1,Gf1h2,Gh2g4,Gf3g5,Gg4h5] We can play the typical kingside attack next.}) (8... b5 $2 9. c5 {[%csl Rb4] The bishop is misplaced.} Ba5 {0-1 Stefansson,V (2496)-Brunello,S (2521) Copenhagen CC GM Ballerup 2022 (5)} 10. e4 {Black can simply resign.} dxe4 (10... Bc7 11. e5 $18) 11. Nxe4 $18 {[%csl Rc6] Serious problems with c6 pawn.}) 9. Rd1 {A very typical preparatory move, we can play e2-e4 confindently only when Black commited to b6, so that c6 is weakened.} (9. e4 {In the game Illescas-Polgar, White rushed to play e4.} Bxd2 10. Nxd2 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 dxe4 {[%cal Gb7b6] And now White doesn't have a good recapture.} 12. Bxe4 (12. Qxe4 e5 $1 $132) 12... Nf6 $132 {[%csl Rd4] ;½-½ Illescas Cordoba,M (2595)-Polgar,J (2630) Dos Hermanas 1995 (1)}) 9... Qe7 (9... b5 10. c5 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nb3 {[%csl Rb4]}) 10. a3 Bd6 11. Re1 $5 {[%csl Re7] Another tricky move, we follow Black's queen.} (11. e4 {seems like a good move, but Black is well prepared to meet it also.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 e5 $132 {White is slightly slightly better, but Black can play.}) 11... e5 {was played in Vaganian-Iordachescu, but it is too early.} (11... Qf8 $146 {is probably Black's best, but nobody played it, White can play in many ways.} 12. b4 $5 {is interesting.} a5 13. c5 Bc7 14. Bb2 e5 {Black will play sooner or later.} 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nd4 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] Typical better positions for White.}) 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. e4 {[%csl Ge1,Re7][%cal Ge1e7] The rook proves to be very useful on the e-file.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Qf8 {1-0 Vaganian,R (2641)-Iordachescu,V (2589) EU-ch 2nd Ohrid 2001 (9)} 16. Bd2 $1 {was much stronger.} Nf6 17. Qc2 e4 {loses the pawn after} (17... exd4 {We are not scared of this, our pieces are much more active.} 18. Nxd4 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8,Gg2]}) 18. Ng5 Bf5 19. Nxe4 $16 {As you have seen, these variations are possible for Black, but quite passive, and with White you need to know the typical ideas.} *

