1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bg2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7] Very solid positional line. Black wants to finish the development, and at some moment play for c7-c5. The only problem for him is that the bishop on b4 is misplaced, but also White's knight on d2 is not fantastic. Very often Black's bishop goes back to e7, and we have a tempo.} 7. O-O Bb7 {Now, we have a choice.} 8. b3 {My recommendation.} (8. Ne5 {a lot of moves are possible. For first view, Ne5 looks active, but for second view it's not so great.} Be7 9. b3 c5 $1 $11 {I have seen that many times, in 1.d4 openings when White plays Ne5, Black's c7-c5 idea becomes stronger.} 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. cxd5 exd5 (11... Nxe5 12. d6 $1) (11... Nxd5 {also possible.}) 12. Ndc4 {looks nice} Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Re8 (13... Rc8 {also possible}) 14. Rc1 Rc8 15. e3 {Black has always a lot of possible moves.} Rc7 16. Qe2 (16. Nd3 {was better maybe, but Black's position is normal} Ne4 $132) 16... Bd6 17. Rfd1 cxd4 18. exd4 $11 {½-½ Dubov,D (2693)-Eljanov,P (2672) Jerusalem Masters rapid 2024 (5) Just equal position}) 8... Nbd7 {According to statistics, this is Black's most common continuation.} (8... Bc3 {It looks strange to me that this move is so rare: it has been tried in just 8 games!} 9. Ba3 $5 {my recommendation.} (9. Rb1 c5 10. Ba3 Ne4 11. dxc5 Bxd2 12. c6 Nxc6 13. Bxf8 Qxf8 14. Nxd2 Nc3 15. Qe1 Nxb1 16. Qxb1 dxc4 17. Nxc4 $11 {absolutely equal}) 9... Bxa1 10. Bxf8 Qxf8 (10... Bxd4 {tempting, but risky:} 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 (11... Bxf2+ $2 {too much} 12. Rxf2 Kxg7 13. Ne5 Nbd7 14. Qa1 $1 Kg8 15. Rf4 $1 $16 {Serious problems for Black.}) 12. Nxd4 c5 13. Nc2 {very playable position, for a long game. For example:} Nc6 14. cxd5 exd5 (14... Nxd5 15. Nc4 $14) 15. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Yf5] Maybe one day we will use the f5 square.}) 11. Qxa1 $36 {/= . I cannot say that we are better, but some small pressure still exists.}) (8... c5 {[%csl Rb4] This is of course an important move. If Black's bishop were on e7, his position would be absolutely fine, but now we can play against the misplaced bishop on b4.} 9. Bb2 Nc6 (9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg2b7] Now our bishop becomes strong:} Nc6 (10... Nbd7 $6 {Mistake:} 11. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 (11... Bxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 13. Nc6 $16) 12. a3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg2b7] the pin is very strong} Be7 13. Nc4 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next, and our pieces are better placed. For computer opinion, the evaluation is +0,90.}) 11. a3 Be7 12. Nxc6 $1 (12. N4f3 {Dubov-Carlsen, but Black's position is normal.} dxc4 $5 $11) 12... Bxc6 13. cxd5 {difficult to believe that Carlsen was planning to play exd5.} Nxd5 (13... exd5 {Possible move, maybe the best, but for a human opinion it is clear that White is slightly better:} 14. Nf3 $14 (14. Qb1 $5 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Yd2f1,Yf1e3] Engine move, with the idea to play Rd1 quickly, and then eventually Nf1-Ne3.})) (13... Bxd5 14. e4 $1 Bb7 15. e5 Nd5 $6 (15... Bxg2 {trans in 13...Nxd5.}) 16. Ne4 $16 {[%cal Gd1g4]}) 14. e4 Nf6 15. e5 Bxg2 16. exf6 Bxf1 17. fxe7 Qxe7 18. Nxf1 $14 {not big advantage, but must be better. Without queens, it's absolutely equal.}) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. a3 $1 {[%csl Rb4] We are in time to get something because Black's bishop is on b4.} Bxd2 (11... Ba5 12. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ra5] Bishop on e5 looks strange.} (12. dxc5 $5 {deserves attention.} bxc5 13. Ne1 $36 {[%cal Ge1d3] Nd3 next.})) 12. Nxd2 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14. Nf3 $14 {For the computer it is equal, but from human perspective, it looks playable.}) 9. Bb2 {Black's position is solid, and many moves are possible. We will analyze the most logical ones.} Rc8 {This is Black's most common continuation.} (9... Qe7 {Looks like a normal move, but Black's bishop on b4 can miss squares soon:} 10. a3 (10. Ne5 {possible, but I don't like this move.}) 10... Bd6 {White has very nice idea:} 11. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Yc4d5,Ye6d5,Gh4f5] White's idea is cxd5-exd5-Nf5.} g6 {logical move to control the f5 square.} 12. cxd5 (12. Nhf3 $5 {deserves attention.}) (12. b4 {looks logical, but after} c5 $1 $11 {[%csl Yh4] Our knight on h4 is bad now. Giri-Caruana, 2024.}) 12... exd5 13. Nc4 $14 {[%csl Rd6] We will take on d6, and play with two bishops.}) (9... Be7 {Possible move, but then we just have a typical 1.d4 position, with an extra tempo because Black has played Bb4-Be7:} 10. cxd5 Bxd5 (10... Nxd5 $6 {Worst recapture because it allows e2-e4.} 11. e4 N5f6 12. Qe2 $14) (10... exd5 {Very typical position. We don't have a big advantage, but we feel that we have White. Many moves are possible, you can just play as you wish:} 11. Rc1 {Human move.} (11. Ne5 {Engine move, with the idea} c5 12. a4 $5 $146 {[%cal Ga4a5] some pressure because a5 is our idea.}) 11... c5 12. Nb1 $5 {[%cal Yb1c3] Nc3 next. Once again, just playable position where it's clear who is White.}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4] We prepare e4.} Ne4 $1 $146 {[%cal Re2e4] against e2-e4.} (11... c5 12. e4 Bb7 13. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Ge4] For sure, White is a bit better.}) 12. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4] /=. Objectively, we are not better, but practically, we feel that we have White. Maybe Nc4 will be our next move, and one day it might be that Ne4+Bd5 construction is not so stable.}) (9... Re8 {[%csl Yf8][%cal Gb4f8] Normal good move. Sometimes, Black will play Bf8.} 10. Rc1 (10. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2] I don't like the queen on c2.} Rc8 11. Rad1 c5 $11 {Giri-Alekseenko, 2020.}) (10. e3 $5 {[%cal Gd1e2] with Qe2 idea. Then Qe2-Rfd1-Rac1 and play.}) 10... a5 (10... Bf8 11. e3 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2] our plan.}) 11. Nb1 $5 {We have time to rotate our knight on c3.} Bf8 {Normal move, the bishop on b4 was mispalced.} 12. Nc3 c6 13. Nd2 $132 {very playable. Next move could be Re1. Here, I feel that I have White color.}) 10. Rc1 Qe7 {Qe7 is better now than at move 9, because thanks to the inclusion of Rc8-Rc1, White's a2-a3 idea is no longer challenging.} (10... c5 {[%csl Rb4] Critical, but we can again play against the bishop on b4:} 11. a3 {If Black takes, we will have two bishops} Bxd2 (11... Ba5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nh4 $16 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gh4f5,Yd2c4]}) 12. Nxd2 cxd4 13. Bxd4 $14 {[%csl Yd4,Yg2] Two bishops.}) 11. e3 {Our idea is to free the e2 square for the queen and continue with Qe2-Rfd1.} (11. a3 {Is not challenging:} Bxa3 12. Bxa3 Qxa3 13. Ra1 Qd6 14. Rxa7 Ra8 $1 $11 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ra7b7,Gd6c6] Rxb7 is not good because of Qc6.}) (11. Rc2 $5 {[%csl Yc1][%cal Yd1c1] Useful move, and it deserves attention. Sometimes we can play Qc1.}) 11... c5 (11... Ne4 {Now a3 is stronger:} 12. a3 Bxa3 (12... Bd6 13. b4 c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. b5 $14 {We have a slightly better position and good chances for a long game.}) 13. Bxa3 Qxa3 14. Ra1 Qd6 15. Rxa7 $14 Ra8 $4 {this idea is no longer possible:} 16. Rxb7 Qc6 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Ng5 $1 $18) (11... Rfd8 12. Qe2 c5 {difficult to say if it is better for Black to play c5 with or without the inclusion of Rfd8-Qe2.} 13. cxd5 {This move is interesting now. We will see later that in Radjabov-Ding, Black's best was} Bxd5 $6 {but here, because of the inclusion of Qe2-Rfd8, we can play} 14. e4 $1 $14 {Of course, Black could have captured on d5 with the knight or with the pawn, but then we would get a standard playable position, as we have seen in many examples during this lesson.}) 12. a3 $5 $146 {Once again, we play against the Bb4.} (12. cxd5 {Was tried in Radjabov-Ding, but Black immediately equalizes:} Bxd5 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxg2 $11) 12... Bxd2 (12... Ba5 13. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Ra5] Black's bishop on a5 can easily be misplaced in the future.}) 13. Nxd2 {Not huge advantage, but practically some chances thanks to two bishops. I feel that I have White here.} cxd4 14. exd4 {Normal position, and it's difficult to guess how your opponent will play.} Ba8 {The strongest for the engine, because Black's bishop will be defended in some important lines.} (14... Rfd8 $6 {Looks normal, but it's a mistake!} 15. b4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c5]} Ba6 {only move} 16. b5 Bb7 17. a4 {White is better. I have tried to check a few logical moves, but I immediately got a lost position for Black:} Ba8 {[%cal Gd5c4] with dxc4 idea.} 18. c5 bxc5 19. Ba3 $18 {Winning position for White.}) 15. Re1 Rfd8 {[%csl Yd2] Our knight on d2 is not fantastic, but I am not sure if we have time to improve it.} 16. Re3 $5 $132 {Sability move. Maybe we don't have an objective advantage, but we have a long game, and we feel that we are White.} *

