1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O b5 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. a3 Be7 10. b3 {This is the critical line for our conception of 5.Nbd2 variation. There are not too many games, so we will create our own theory.} Bb7 {This is the most critical line, in my opinion.} (10... f6 $2 {[%csl Rf6] Remember: f6 is f6 :)} 11. bxc4 $1 fxe5 (11... Nc3 12. Qe1 $16 {[%csl Ra8]}) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. dxe5 $16 {White is seriously better.}) (10... c3 $146 {It's novelty, and it's not particularly good, but it's better to check it.} 11. Nb1 {[%cal Ge2e4] we are ready for e4.} f6 {Now, f6 looks necessary.} 12. Ng4 $1 {[%csl Yg4][%cal Yg4e3] Best square for our knight, which will probably go on e3 soon.} (12. Nd3 $6 {Logical move, but Black is fine after} Nc6 $1 13. e4 $2 (13. e3 Bb7 $13 {Not easy to take pawn back}) 13... Nxd4 $17 {we can face many unpleasant surprises}) 12... b4 13. axb4 Bxb4 14. Ba3 $36 {[%csl Yc3] For sure we'll recover the pawn, and we will have a typical structural advantage. The position is fresh, and very pleasant to play for White.}) (10... Ba6 $5 $146 11. Qc2 $5 {This looks stronger than bxc4.} c5 $1 {Critical.} (11... cxb3 {We are not afraid of this move, because after} 12. Nxb3 $16 {[%csl Ra6] Black's bishop on a6 is misplaced.}) 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Ne4 $5 Be7 {No need to take bxc4, because after dxc4, Black's bishop becomes stronger.} (13... Bd4 $4 {Black falls in our trap.} 14. Ng5 {And our position is winning:} g6 15. Nexf7 $1 Rxf7 16. Nxe6 $18) 14. Bb2 {We can play for the initiative.} f6 {But when Black plays f6, which looks the best in this concrete position, then bxc4 becomes stronger. Why? Just because we have provoked the move f6, which in the long-term can be problematic for Black.} 15. bxc4 bxc4 16. Nxc4 $14 (16. Bh3 $5 {deserves attention.})) (10... cxb3 {This is a natural move for Black, but it's absolutely clear that White has at least the full compensation.} 11. Nxb3 {Maybe I would go for Nxb3, but it doesn't mean that it's the best: both moves are fine.} (11. Qxb3 {It's very difficult to say if Qxb3 or Nxb3 is the best.} Qe8 {Black's best, according to the engine, but nobody has ever tried it.} (11... a5 $5 {Looks normal} 12. Bb2 {Good news for us that our opponent has a lot of options. According to my experience, when I have a lot of options, I will chose the worst one :)} Ra6 {only computer knows why Ra6. Usually, our move could be e4 or Nd3 after any Black's move.} 13. Nd3 $5 (13. e4 $5 a4 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. Rfc1 c6 16. h4 $5 {Just wait his moves.} Bb7 (16... h6 17. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3] sometimes, we will be ready for g4.}) 17. Nd3 Nbd7 18. e5 Nd5 19. Nc5 Ra7 (19... Nxc5 20. dxc5 {[%cal Gd2e4,Ge4d6] Ne4-Nd6 next.}) 20. Nxb7 (20. Nde4 $5 {also possible}) 20... Rxb7 21. Qxc6 {minimum we can recover the pawn}) 13... c6 {Finally he will play c6 at some point.} 14. Rac1 $44 {our plan is e4-h5-h5. It's not attack, but could be attack in future.}) (11... c5 $6 {c5 is logical, but bad.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bb2 Bb7 14. Rfd1 $5 {It is more tricky than 14.Ne4 played by GM Oparin, for example:} (14. Ne4 Be7 15. Rfd1 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Nc3 Qb6 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 {½-½ Oparin,G (2613)-Gavrilescu,D (2467) EU-ch 20th Skopje 2019 (4) White recovered the pawn, but lost all the advantage.}) 14... Be7 15. Ndc4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc4e3] super move with Ne3 idea.}) 12. Bb2 Nc6 13. Nd3 $5 $44 {We play for compensation.} (13. Bxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 $13 {I don't believe that Black can go here confidently, but for the engine this is fine.})) 11... a5 {Best and logical.} 12. Qc2 $5 {[%cal Gb3c5] my idea is to support Nc5 in case of a4.} (12. Bb2 $6 {mistake because of} a4 $1 {we don't want to go on d2, and after} 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. dxc5 f6 $1 {important move.} 15. Nd3 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6] Good place for knight, and Black's position is very comfortable.}) 12... a4 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. Qxc5 {[%csl Gc5] White's position looks very interesting and playable. For example:} Nd7 15. Nxd7 Bxd7 16. e4 Nb6 17. Bf4 Rc8 18. Bd2 $1 {in case of Nc4 we can play Bb4.} f5 (18... Nc4 19. Bb4 $14 {[%csl Gb4] Very nice place for our bishop.}) 19. Bb4 Rf7 {If I say that White is better, a lot of people will believe, but it's unclear.} 20. Rfe1 fxe4 21. Bxe4 h6 $36 {Objectively, we are not better, but the position is very playable and we have a practical initiative.}) 11. Qc2 $5 $146 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Rd5c3,Gc2c3] This is the most interesting move, in my opinion. Our idea is to stop Nc3.} (11. bxc4 {Was played in all the three games that have reached this position, but after} Nc3 12. Qe1 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 $11 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gb5c4] Black is at least fine after both 13...Na4 or 13...bxc4.}) 11... c3 $1 {The best and the most critical move.} (11... cxb3 12. Nxb3 $44 {[%cal Yb8d7,Ge5c6] Just typical good compensation for White. Black's best is 12...Nd7, where after 13.Nc6, it's clear that White has all the fun.}) 12. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c3] Of course, if we can just play Nxc3, our position will be better, that's why Black has to go for} b4 13. axb4 Na6 $1 {I don't think that Black is objectively worse here, but we need to create the maximum amount of practical problems.} 14. Ba3 $5 (14. Nxc3 {I don't like it, because it allows a lot of exchanges:} Ndxb4 15. Qd1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 c5 $11 {Equal, but most important: Black has a very easy play.}) 14... Naxb4 (14... Bxb4 $6 15. Bxb4 Naxb4 16. Qc1 $14 {[%cal Ge4c5] Nc5 next, and White's position is better.}) 15. Bxb4 (15. Qc1 a5 16. Nxc3 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qd5+ 19. Kg1 c5 $11 {Black plays c5, and the position is equal.}) 15... Bxb4 {White can try different moves, but my favorite one is} 16. Nc5 (16. h4 $5 {always useful move, and you can play it because it leads to a very complicated game:} c6 {computer move} 17. Nc5 Qc7 18. Ned3 a5 19. Rfc1 $44 {White doesn't have advantage, but for sure he has compensation. The position is very complex and open for all three results.}) 16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 {Black needs to find Qg5, otherwise he will have small problems.} Qg5 {Black's best, according to the engine.} (17... a5 {Human move} 18. c6 Ba6 $6 19. Rfd1 $16 {serious advantage}) (17... Nb4 18. Qxc3 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qd5+ 20. f3 {If you just look at the engine's evaluation, you will think that Black is absolutely fine, but from a human point of view it looks like White has some pressure. For example:} Qb7 {not so simple move} (20... Nc6 21. Nxc6 Qxc6 22. Ra5 $14 {We are better. I want to say that it's easy for Black to go wrong.}) 21. Qc4 Nd5 22. Kf2 Rfb8 23. Ra3 $14 {game continues}) 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxc3 a5 $1 {The best, but it's not so easy to play a5, in my opinion. We have a lot of possibilities, but no advantage:} 20. f4 $5 (20. Ra3 $5 {[%cal Gf1a1]} Rfb8 21. Re1 $132 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 idea}) (20. Nc4 {solid move} Bxc4 21. Qxc4 Rfb8 22. Ra4 Qd5 $11) 20... Qh5 (20... Qf5 $6 21. Ra4 {[%cal Ge2e4,Yd5e4,Yg3g4] Our idea is e4-Bxe4-g4.} h5 22. Re1 $14) 21. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} f6 22. e4 fxe5 23. exd5 exf4 24. dxe6 $11 {Black has played very well, and the position is equal now. Don't forget two things: - we are analyzing an absolutely new position, and it will require a lot of years before the theory arrives at this point; - you can always choose to play a move like 16.h4, for example, to have a complicated game where your opponent cannot make a draw just by memorizing the engine's lines.} *

